<title>GEORGIA ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION DIVISION AND THE U. S.
COAST GUARD SIGN AGREEMENT TO REMOVE HAZARDOUS BATTERIES FROM
GEORGIA&#146;S NAVIGABLE WATERWAYS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body stylesrc="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/EPD/index.htm">
<p align="center"><font size="4"><b>JIM USSERY</b></font></p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><b>404-656-2833</b></font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4"><b>&#160;</b></font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4"><b><u>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:</u></b></font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4"><b>&#160;</b></font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4"><b>GEORGIA ENVIRONMENTAL
PROTECTION DIVISION AND THE U. S. COAST GUARD SIGN AGREEMENT TO
REMOVE HAZARDOUS BATTERIES FROM GEORGIA&#146;S NAVIGABLE
WATERWAYS</b></font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4"><b>December 13, 1996 - Atlanta,
Georgia. </b>Many of Georgia&#146;s waterways are navigated
through the assistance of Coast Guard Aids to Navigation Stations
or lighted beacons. These facilities are powered by disposable
zinc-air depolarized batteries containing mercury. Over the years
(1960-1980), as these facilities were being serviced, batteries
were sometimes dumped overboard or batteries were dumped into the
water by vandals or from vessels colliding with beacons. Under
the terms of a Consent Agreement executed on December 4, 1996
with the Georgia Environmental Protection Division, the Coast
Guard will investigate and clean up all Coast Guard maintained
Aids to Navigation sites in Georgia.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4">The clean up requires Coast Guard
and Navy frogmen to sift through ocean and river sediment by
hand. The batteries and battery parts are then loaded onto a
Coast Guard vessel and shipped as hazardous waste for reclamation
(to recover material value). The final phase of the project will
be the sampling of sediment from sites to determine the extent,
if any, of sediment remediation. </font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4">To keep this problem from
recurring, the Coast Guard has developed a solar powered Aid to
Navigation to replace the battery operated unit. Although this
new design will need a battery backup, the new battery will be a
lead-acid battery which is rechargeable and recyclable. This new
design will be piloted in Georgia and Florida and will eliminate
the generation of hazardous waste batteries in the future.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="4">To date the following work has
been accomplished pursuant to the terms of the Agreement:</font></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="left"><font size="4">&#183; 286 aquatic
                sites have been surveyed and approximately 2,401
                batteries and associated battery parts were
                removed</font></p>
                <p align="left"><font size="4">&#160;</font></p>
                <p align="left"><font size="4">&#183; 21
                terrestrial sites have been surveyed and 324
                batteries and associated battery parts have been
                removed</font></p>
                <p align="left"><font size="4">&#160;</font></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p><font size="4">&#183; Over 163,000 pounds of
                hazardous waste batteries and battery parts have
                been removed from Georgia&#146;s waterways and
                manifested to a hazardous waste reclamation
                facility.</font></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
