<html>
<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>GEORGIA ANNOUNCES DRAFT INTERSTATE WATER COMPACT</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body stylesrc="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/EPD/index.htm">
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica"><b><u>FOR IMMEDIATE
RELEASE:</u></b></font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica"><b>&#160;</b></font></p>
<p align="center"><font face="Helvetica"><b>GEORGIA ANNOUNCES
DRAFT INTERSTATE WATER COMPACT</b></font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica"><b>December 11, 1996 -
Atlanta, Georgia.</b> Following three months of negotiations
which began in September 1996, representatives of the States of
Alabama, Florida, and Georgia have reached agreement on the
wording of two interstate water compacts. One compact is for the
Apalachicola, Chattahoochee, and Flint (ACF) River Basins in
Georgia, Florida, and Alabama. The other is for the Alabama,
Coosa, and Tallapoosa (ACT) River Basins in Georgia and Alabama.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">Governor Zell Miller
appointed Georgia&#146;s negotiators: Joe Tanner, former
Commissioner of the Department of Natural Resources and currently
Director of the Governor&#146;s Commission on Privatization; and
Harold Reheis, Director of the Environmental Protection Division
(EPD) of the Georgia Department of Natural Resources. They are
assisted by Law Department attorneys representing Attorney
General Mike Bowers.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">The two compacts are
intended to help provide a long-lasting, peaceable agreement
among the three States and the federal government over management
and use of the water resources in the ACF and ACT river basins.
The compacts are one result of a comprehensive water resources
study being conducted jointly by Alabama, Florida, and Georgia
and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">The state negotiators
intend to request that the legislatures of Georgia, Alabama, and
Florida adopt the compacts during their 1997 legislative
sessions. Once this is done, the States intend to send the
compacts to Washington, D.C. for ratification by the Congress
before the end of 1997.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">The compacts would allow
for the apportioning of the waters of these river basins among
the three states, but the negotiations on how to apportion them
would not occur until 1998.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">The compacts contain the
following features:</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">The Governors of
        each state would serve as the Compact Commissioners and
        could appoint alternates to represent them.</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">The President of
        the United States would appoint a Federal Commissioner
        and alternates.</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">Only the State
        Commissioners would be able to vote, and all decisions
        must be unanimous.</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<p align="left"><font face="WP TypographicSymbols">!</font><font
face="Helvetica"> The Commission&#146;s powers would include the
abilities to:</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#176;
                receive and spend funds;</font></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <blockquote>
            <blockquote>
                <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#176;
                hire and fire staff or contractors;</font></p>
                <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#176;
                enter agreements and contracts;</font></p>
                <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#176;
                plan for, study, and monitor the waters of these
                basins; </font></p>
                <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#176;
                develop and own water resource facilities; and</font></p>
                <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#176;
                establish and modify a water allocation formula.</font></p>
                <p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
            </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">The compacts also provide
for representatives of the federal government to participate in
the development of any water allocation formula. Once the states
have unanimously agreed to a formula, the Federal Commissioner
could either approve it or disapprove it. Approval would put the
allocation formula in effect; disapproval would nullify and
dissolve the interstate compacts.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">There would be no
impairment or adverse effect on any constitutional authority of
the United States, nor would any existing federal law be changed
or affected by a compact. Existing federal laws include the Clean
Water Act, the National Environmental Policy Act, the Endangered
Species Act, and the acts that authorized the construction and
operation of the various Corps of Engineers reservoirs.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">The ACT and ACF Compacts
would be the first of their kind in the southeast. Twenty-six
interstate water compacts exist around the nation, and most have
been used to settle disputes over water rights in western states.
Only one compact exists for a river basin in the east: the
Delaware River Basin Compact, which includes the states of New
York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Delaware.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">The benefits of the
proposed compacts would be to provide an end to water disputes
among Georgia, Florida and Alabama, and to provide for better
coordination and management of these vital water resources fo the
betterment of the water users in all three states.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">For further information,
contact Harold Reheis at 404/656-4713 or Joe Tanner at
404/657-2200.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
</body>
</html>
