<p>391-3-20-.15<a href="#Repairs-14"> Repairs and Retests</a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.16 <a href="#Extension-16">Extensions, Reciprocal
Tests</a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.17<a href="#Waivers-17"> Waivers</a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.18 <a href="#Sale-18">Sale of Vehicles</a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.19 <a href="#Management-19">Management Contractor</a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.20 <a href="#Referee-20">Referee Program</a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.21 <a href="#Fees-21">Inspection Fees</a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.22 <a href="#Enforcement-22">Enforcement</a> <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Definitions"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.01 Definitions. Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>The following terms as used in these rules shall have the
meaning hereinafter respectively ascribed, except that to the
extent terms are not defined in these rules, the Act's
definitions control; and provided that definitions within any subsequent
rule or subdivision thereof, which are expressly made applicable
to the rule or subdivision within which they appear, shall apply
for purposes of such specific rule or subdivision thereof. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) &quot;Act&quot; means O.C.G.A. 12-9-40 et seq., as
amended, &quot;The Georgia Motor Vehicle Emission Inspection and
Maintenance Act.&quot; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) &quot;ASM test&quot; means an Acceleration Simulation Mode
exhaust emission test. This test shall be conducted using a
chassis dynamometer. The test procedure shall be defined in the
I/M Test Manual. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(c) &quot;Calibration&quot; means the process of establishing
or verifying the response curve of the emissions analyzer using
the applicable calibration gases. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(d) &quot;Certificate of Emission Inspection&quot; means a
serially numbered form indicating that a motor vehicle has been
inspected under the requirements established by Chapter
391-3-20-.04 and 391-3-20-.05 of these Rules. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(e) &quot;Department&quot; means the Department of Natural
Resources. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(f) &quot;Director&quot; means the Director of the
Environmental Protection Division of the Department of Natural
Resources. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(g) &quot;Emissions Analyzer&quot; means a device for
measuring the concentration of certain exhaust gases emitted by a
motor vehicle. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(h) &quot;Emission Inspection&quot; means all tests and
inspections required to determine that a vehicle is not producing
excessive emissions, including an exhaust emission test,
evaporative emission test, a tampering inspection, checks of on-board diagnostic
information, compliance with emission recalls and other tests
required by these rules. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(i) &quot;Exhaust Emissions Test&quot; means the determination
of the amount of specified gases in a vehicle's exhaust, using
the procedures specified in Section 391-3-20-0.32-.04. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(j) &quot;EPA Rules&quot; means 40 CFR Part 51, Subpart S,
including appendices, and 40 CFR Part 85, Subpart W, including
appendices, as of July 1, 1996. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(k) &quot;EPD&quot; means the Environmental Protection
Division of the Georgia Department of Natural Resources. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(l) &quot;Gas Calibration&quot; means the calibration of an
emission analyzer by the use of a manufactured calibration gas. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(m) &quot;Gray Market Vehicle&quot; means a vehicle which was
not certified to meet U.S. emission standards, but which was
imported into the United States under a waiver of the emission requirements. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(n) &quot;GVWR&quot; means the gross vehicle weight rating,
i.e., the weight of the vehicle and contents when loaded to its
maximum capacity, as established by the vehicle manufacturer. </p>

<p>(o) &quot;Hot Rod&quot; means a vehicle in which the original
engine has been replaced with an engine from another
manufacturer, or with a different type of engine from the same
manufacturer which was never installed in that model vehicle. For
the purposes of this definition, a different type of engine will
include engines with a different number of cylinders from any
engine which was originally installed in that make of vehicle. It
will not include engines of the same family, e.g., Chevrolet V8s of
283, 305, 327, 350 and 400 cubic inch displacement, nor will it
include engines different from the original, but which were also
installed in that make of vehicle, e.g., gasoline for diesel
engine swaps in General Motors or Volkswagen vehicles, or V8 for
V6 swaps where both engines were installed in that model vehicle
by the manufacturer for retail sale. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(p) &quot;I/M Test Manual&quot; means the Georgia Department
of Natural Resources <strong>Enhanced Inspection/Maintenance Test
Equipment, Procedures and Specifications</strong>, dated July 12, 1996. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(q) &quot;Inspector&quot; means a person approved by the
Department to perform the emission inspections required by the
Act. Inspectors certified under the provisions of Section
391-3-11 must satisfy the requirements of this section in order
to be certified to perform inspections required under this section. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(r) &quot;Kit Car&quot; means a motor vehicle which does not
utilize a chassis from a vehicle certified to meet emission
control standards or for which the original manufacturer's
identification has been eliminated due to the replacement of the vehicle's
body with one of a different make and/or style. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(s) &quot;Light Duty Truck&quot; means any motor vehicle with
a GVWR of 8500 pounds or less which is a light duty truck as
defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
Pickups and vans are included in this class of vehicle. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(t) &quot;Light Duty Vehicle&quot; means a passenger car or
passenger car derivative, as defined by the United States
Environmental Protection Agency . <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(u) &quot;Management Contractor&quot; means the person or
corporation contracted by the Director to design and operate the
program data management system and to perform certain other
program functions. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(v) &quot;Model year&quot; means the model year of a vehicle
as designated by the vehicle manufacturer. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(w) &quot;Newer vehicles&quot; means vehicles with a
designated model year which is of the current test year and up to
five (5) years older than the current test year. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(x) &quot;Off-year inspection&quot; means an inspection which
is performed in a year (odd or even) in which an inspection is
not normally required for that model year vehicle. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(y) &quot;Older vehicles&quot; means vehicles with a
designated model year which is more than (5) five years older
than the current test year. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(z) &quot;On-board Diagnostic (OBD) System&quot; means a
system installed on 1996 or later model year vehicles as required
by Section 202(m) of the Clean Air Act (42 U.S.C. 7521) which is
designed to identify engine or emission control system problems
which cause excessive emissions. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(aa) &quot;Owner&quot; means the registered owner or the
individual presenting the responsible motor vehicle for the
emission inspection required under the Act. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(bb) &quot;Owner of Station&quot; means the individual,
partnership, firm, corporation, association, municipality,
governmental agency, or lessee having control of the daily
operation of an inspection station and having responsibility for
the emission inspections. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(cc) &quot;Primary Emission Control Component&quot; means the
catalytic convertor, air injection system, exhaust gas
recirculation system or other major component, as determined by
the Director, which is installed on a vehicle primarily for the purpose
of emission control. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(dd) &quot;Recognized Repair Technician&quot; means any person
professionally engaged in vehicle repair, employed by an ongoing
business whose purpose is vehicle repair or possessing a
nationally recognized certification for vehicle emission related
diagnosis and repair. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(ee) &quot;Regular inspection&quot; means an inspection
performed in a test year (odd or even) in which an inspection is
normally due for that model year vehicle. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(ff) &quot;State Inspection Program&quot; means the program of
vehicle emission inspections as required by the Act. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(gg) &quot;Test Cycle&quot; means the test year in which an
inspection is due and any subsequent years for which the
inspection can be used for registration. For regular inspections,
this will be the test year and the following year. For off-year inspections,
this will be either the test year or the test year and the two
following years, as provided for by Chapter 391-3-20-.12(5). </p>

<p>(hh) &quot;Test Year&quot; means a period running from the
conclusion of one vehicle registration season to the conclusion
of the next year's registration season, except that the 1997 test
year shall run from October 1, 1996 to June 30, 1997. The 1998
test year shall run from July 1, 1997 to December 31, 1998. All subsequent
test years shall be concurrent with the calendar year. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(ii) &quot;2-speed idle test&quot; means an exhaust emission
test as defined in the I/M Test Manual. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Covered"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.02 Covered Counties. Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>The requirements of this Chapter apply to vehicles in the
following designated counties: <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) Cherokee; </p>

<p>(b) Clayton; </p>

<p>(c) Cobb; </p>

<p>(d) Coweta; </p>

<p>(e) DeKalb; </p>

<p>(f) Douglas; </p>

<p>(g) Fayette; </p>

<p>(h) Forsyth; </p>

<p>(i) Fulton; </p>

<p>(j) Gwinnett; </p>

<p>(k) Henry; </p>

<p>(l) Paulding; </p>

<p>(m) Rockdale. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="covveh"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.03 Covered Vehicles; Exemptions. Amended. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) The requirements of this chapter apply to the following
classes of gasoline-powered motor vehicles registered in covered
counties: <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) All 1975 and newer model year light duty vehicles. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) All 1975 and newer model year light duty trucks with a
gross vehicle weight rating of 8500 pounds or less. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) The requirements of this chapter also apply to the
following vehicles in the classes listed above which are operated
in covered counties: <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) Vehicles which are operated by a federal or state agency,
municipality or other political subdivision in a covered county. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) Vehicles which are operated for more than 60 days per year
on federal installations located in a covered county. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) Vehicles which are capable of being operated on both
gasoline and any alternate fuel are covered by the inspection
requirements, and shall be tested on gasoline. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) New vehicles are exempt from testing until the test year
two years following the model year of the vehicle. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(5) EPD may require that any vehicle registered or operated in
the covered counties but which is claimed to be not subject to
the requirements of the emission inspection program, be presented
for verification that the vehicle is not subject. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(6) For vehicles which do not have the original engine, the
model year of the chassis will be considered the model year of
the vehicle. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(7) For kit cars, the model of the vehicle shall be deemed to
be the model year of the vehicle as established in the vehicle
registration database maintained by the Georgia Department of
Revenue. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(8) Grandfather provisions for gray market vehicles, kit cars,
and hot rods. Owners of vehicles which qualify as gray market
vehicles, kit cars, or which have hot rod engine swaps may
request special test standards as described in Section 391-3-20-.05,
at the time of the vehicle's first inspection under the enhanced inspection/
maintenance program requirements. Such vehicles will be subject
to the special standards at subsequent inspections. Vehicles
which are tested under the regular procedures and standards at
their first enhanced program inspection, or which are newly registered
in the covered counties after December 31, 1998, are not eligible
for the special standards. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(9) A vehicle which is otherwise subject to the provisions of
these rules is exempt from inspection if it: </p>

<p>(a) is driven less than 5,000 miles per year, is 10 years old
or older and is owned by a person 65 years old or older, or <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) is an antique or collector car or truck 25 years old or
older. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Proceedures"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.04 Emission Inspection Procedures. Amended. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Prior to testing, inspectors will determine whether the
vehicle has leaking fluids or tires with cords exposed, is
overheating, or is otherwise unsafe to test. Inspectors will also
make a determination of whether the vehicle has been subject to
any emission recall campaigns for which the initial owner
notification occurred after January 1, 1995, and whether or not
the inspections, parts replacements or other actions required by
the recall campaign have been performed. EPD may modify or waive
this requirement if it finds that information needed to make this
determination is not readily available to inspection stations. A
vehicle which is unsafe to test or which has not complied with
emission recall campaigns shall be rejected from testing. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) Covered vehicles which are not rejected will receive the
following tests and inspections: <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) A tampering inspection of the catalytic converter. All
vehicles which were originally equipped with a catalytic
convertor shall have a convertor installed. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) An exhaust emission test. For newer vehicles, a 2-speed
idle test as established in the I/M Test Manual shall be
performed. For older vehicles, an ASM test as established in the
I/M Test Manual shall be performed. Full-time four-wheel-drive
vehicles, regardless of model year, shall be tested using the 2-speed
idle test procedure. For the 1997 test year only, all vehicles
shall be tested using the 2-speed idle test procedure. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(c) An evaporative emission system functional test. For the
1997 and 1998 test years, this will be a gas cap test as
established in the I/M Test Manual. For subsequent years, this
will be a gas cap test or other test as established in the I/M
Test Manual. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(d) For 1996 and later model vehicles so equipped, a check of
the on-board diagnostic system to detect any emission control
system problems, on vehicles where such a system was originally installed. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) Vehicles which stall three times during the test shall
fail the inspection. Vehicles which overheat or otherwise become
unsafe to test shall fail the test. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) The station operator shall take all reasonable precautions
to avoid damage to vehicles during the inspection. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(5) EPD may require alternate procedures for certain types or
classes of vehicles when it determines that such alternate
procedures are necessary to safely and effectively test such
vehicles. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(6) The station operator shall comply with all requirements
established in the I/M Test Manual. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Standards"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.05 Emission Standards. Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Vehicles must meet the following standards in order to
pass the emission inspection. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) Tampering <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>For vehicles which were equipped with a catalytic converter or
convertors when produced by the manufacturer, the convertor(s)
must be installed. Vehicles which have been converted to a dual exhaust
system may meet this requirement by having a catalytic convertor
installed in each pipe of the exhaust system. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) Exhaust emissions tests <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>1. 2-speed idle test <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>For any vehicle which is subject to the 2-speed idle test
procedure, the vehicle shall pass the exhaust emission test if,
in each mode, any simultaneous pair of values for hydrocarbons
and carbon monoxide does not exceed the exhaust levels
established in the I/M Test Manual. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>2. ASM exhaust emission tests <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>For any vehicle which is subject to the ASM test procedure,
the vehicle shall pass the exhaust emission test if the values
for hydrocarbons, oxides of nitrogen and carbon monoxide do not exceed
those established in the I/M Test Manual. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(i) Phase-in standards - Vehicles which are tested or retested
between July 1, 1997 and December 31, 1997 shall not exceed the
exhaust emission levels established in the I/M Test Manual. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(ii) Final Standards - For all tests and retests performed
after December 31, 1997, the exhaust emission standards
established in the I/M Test Manual must not be exceeded. </p>

<p>(c) Gas cap pressure test <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>All vehicles subject to testing under these rules shall pass a
gas cap pressure test as defined in the I/M Test Manual. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) Vehicles which are grandfathered as gray market vehicles,
kit cars or hot rods shall pass the following standards. For 1985
and newer model vehicles, the vehicle shall pass the exhaust emission
standards for 1981 model vehicles of the same type. For 1984 and
older model vehicles, the vehicle shall pass the exhaust emission
standards for 1975 model vehicles of the same type. Grandfathered vehicles
are not required to pass the visual inspection for tampering,
except that hot rod vehicles shall be equipped with a catalytic convertor
(or convertors on vehicles with dual exhausts), unless neither
the original vehicle nor replacement engine was so equipped. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) If the vehicle has been the subject of an emissions recall
campaign, the vehicle shall have had all inspections, repairs or
modifications required by the recall campaign performed. This
provision shall not apply to grandfathered vehicles. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) Vehicles which are equipped with on-board diagnosis (OBD)
systems shall have no fault codes indicating problems in
emissions control parameters monitored by the OBD system. </p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Onroad"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.06 On-Road Testing. Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Covered vehicles are expected to meet emission standards
at all times. Vehicles which appear at any time, on the basis of
remote sensing device readings or other methods established by
the Director, to not be meeting the appropriate emission
standards may be required to be presented for an emission inspection
under Sections 391-3-20-.04 and 391-3-20-.05. Vehicles which fail such
inspection shall be required to be reinspected and pass such
reinspection as provided for by Section 391-3-20-.15. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) The Director shall establish remote sensing inspection
procedures and standards which will identify vehicles that have a
high probability of exceeding the emission standards in Section 391-3-20-.05,
and may establish other procedures and standards which will
identify such vehicles. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) The Director shall cause to be performed annually remote
sensing tests equal to at least 0.5% of the covered vehicle
population. Vehicles which are identified as failing the remote
sensing standards twice at any time following the vehicle's last
regularly scheduled emission inspection shall be presumed to be
high polluting vehicles. Owners of such presumed high polluting
vehicles shall be notified by mail that their vehicle has been so
identified. Notifications shall not be mailed for vehicles which:
1) have already received such a notification since the last
regular emission inspection, but passed the on-road program
reinspection or 2) received a waiver at the either the last
regular inspection or at a subsequent on-road program
reinspection. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) Owners of vehicles receiving such a notification shall
present the vehicle for an on-road program reinspection at any
appropriate inspection station within 30 days following receipt
of the notification. The vehicle shall receive the full inspection
that would be required for that vehicle for the test year during
which the notification was sent. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(5) If the vehicle passes the initial on-road program
reinspection, the reinspection shall be performed at no cost to
the vehicle owner. The station performing the reinspection shall
be reimbursed for the cost of the reinspection by EPD. If the vehicle
fails the initial on-road program reinspection, the vehicle owner
shall pay the cost of the on-road program reinspection. Payment
of the inspection fee shall entitle the vehicle owner to also
obtain one additional free reinspection. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(6) Vehicles failing the on-road program shall be repaired and
retested as provided for by Section 391-3-20-.15, within 30 days
of the initial on-road reinspection. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(7) For vehicles which are notified of a reinspection within
one calendar year of the date that the next regular inspection
would be due for that vehicle and which either pass the on-road reinspection
(on either the initial or subsequent reinspection) or obtain a
waiver, the vehicle shall be deemed to have met the inspection
requirement for the next regularly scheduled inspection. Such vehicles shall
be given an inspection sticker and Certificate which reflect that this inspection requirement
has been met. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(8) Vehicle owners shall be deemed in violation of these rules
if they do not: a) obtain an on-road program reinspection within
30 days of receiving a notification under paragraph (3) of this
section or b) either pass a reinspection or obtain a waiver
within 60 days of notification. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Equipspec"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.07 Inspection Equipment System Specifications.
Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Test equipment systems must be approved by EPD. </p>

<p>(a) EPD will approve equipment which meets all specifications
established in the I/M Test Manual. Manufacturers of test
equipment shall apply to EPD for approval of test systems which
meet these specifications. Operators of inspection stations may
select from any system approved by EPD. Stations may elect to
become a regular test station, which may test any covered vehicle,
or a newer vehicle-only station, which may test only those
vehicles up to six model years old. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) Regular test stations shall acquire a test system which
meets the Acceleration Simulation Mode (ASM) requirements of
these rules and the I/M Test Manual. Prior to July 1, 1997,
regular test stations need to acquire only a test system which
meets the 2-speed idle requirements of these rules and other
requirements established by the Director. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(c) Newer vehicle-only test stations shall acquire a test
system which meets the 2-speed idle requirements of these rules
and the I/M Test Manual. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Qualitycontrol"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.08 Quality Control and Equipment Calibration
Procedures. Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) All test equipment shall, at a minimum, be calibrated
according to the procedures and schedules specified in the I/M
Test Manual, as consistent with Subpart S, Appendix A of the EPA rules,
or other procedures and schedules established by the Director. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) Station owners shall meet the quality control requirements
established in the I/M Test Manual. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Stationreq"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.09 Inspection Station Requirements. Amended. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Classes of stations - There shall be three classes of test
stations: Two types of public test stations - Regular test
stations, and Newer vehicle-only test stations - and Fleet test
stations. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) Newer Vehicle-Only Test Stations <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>1. Newer vehicle-only test stations are authorized to inspect
only newer vehicles. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>2. Newer vehicle-only test stations shall operate approved
test equipment which is capable of performing the 2-speed idle
test described by these rules. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) Regular Test Stations <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>1. Regular test stations are authorized to inspect any vehicle
subject to the inspection program. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>2. Regular test stations shall operate approved test equipment
which is capable of performing both the 2-speed idle test and ASM
test described by these rules. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(c) Fleet Test Stations <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>1. Vehicle owners who operate a vehicle fleet engaged in
commercial activity, utility service or government service or
businesses which are engaged in the sale, rental or leasing of
motor vehicles may be licensed to inspect their own vehicles, but
must meet certain additional requirements beyond those established
for public regular or newer vehicle-only test stations. Only
fleet test station operators are allowed to test vehicles that
they own or operate, with the exception that public station
operators may test not more than ten (10) vehicles which are owned
incidental to the operation of their business. </p>

<p>2. Fleet test stations may choose to test either newer
vehicles only or to test all vehicles, and shall acquire the
appropriate test system. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) General Inspection Station Requirements <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) Persons wishing to obtain a Certificate of Authorization
to operate one or more inspection stations shall apply to EPD in
a format established by EPD. Such application shall include all information
needed to determine that the proposed station(s) will meet the
requirements of these Rules. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) Station owners must obtain all permits and licenses
necessary for the establishment of inspection stations. The
station shall conform to all applicable federal, state and local
code requirements including, but not limited to, planning and
building codes, carbon monoxide levels, ventilation, safety and fire regulations. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(c) EPD may approve mobile test stations for the purpose of
testing fleet or car dealer vehicles subject to the program at
the fleet or car dealer location. Mobile test stations that are
awarded Certificates of Authorization shall comply with all requirements
for mobile testing as established in the I/M Test Manual. Mobile test
stations shall provide EPD or the Management Contractor with advance notice
of scheduled testing of fleet or car dealer vehicles and shall
update such notice as the scheduled testing is changed. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(d) Public test stations shall provide an area adequate to
allow four (4) vehicles per test lane to wait for testing. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(e) Each station shall display a sign approved by EPD that
indicates that the facility is a State Emission Inspection
Station. The sign shall be located in an easily visible location.
All sign locations must meet any State and local code requirements. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(f) Lanes at each inspection station must be of adequate
length, width and height to accommodate all normal-sized vehicles
which are presented for inspection. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(g) Adequate protection must be provided for the testing and
data handling equipment to allow for operations within
specifications in all weather conditions. Any component of the
testing and data handling equipment which affects the test results
shall not be subject to temperatures beyond its manufacturer's specifications
for such equipment. All equipment will be maintained in like-new condition. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(h) Each public test station shall provide to customers: <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>1. A public waiting area which will allow a motorist to
observe the test of his or her vehicle; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>2. Response to inquiries and complaints in person and over the
telephone during business hours; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>3. EPD public information materials; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>4. Information provided by EPD on repair facilities and on
their performance in repairing vehicles which have failed the
emission inspections. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(i) Stations will be required to obtain a data transmission
line to tie into the Management Contractor's database, shall be
provided access to the Management Contractor's database and shall
transmit all vehicle inspection data and quality assurance data
that is collected by the Management Contractor. The format of the
data transmittal shall be compatible with the Management Contractor's
database. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(j) Stations shall be required to pay a per-paid-test program
administration fee. This fee will be collected through the sale
of Certificate of Emission Inspection forms or other method
determined by the Director. This fee will cover the cost to administer
the program, including: 1) the services of the Management Contractor,
2) the cost of EPD administration, 3) the cost to affected county
tax offices of monitoring vehicle registrations, and 4) any other costs
attributable to the program. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(k) Liability Insurance <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>1. Station owners conducting only 2-speed idle tests shall
provide proof of $10,000 liability insurance for the period of
the Certificate. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>2. Station owners conducting ASM tests shall provide proof of
garage owner's liability insurance, with a garage keeper's
endorsement, or equivalent liability coverage as determined and
approved by the Director, for the period of the Certificate. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(l) Operation hours shall be posted at each public test
station on the station's State Inspection Program sign. Stations
shall provide inspections at all times during the posted hours.
Public test stations may provide inspections by appointment only
but shall indicate such on the station's State Inspection Program
sign. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) Additional Requirements for Fleet Test Stations <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) A waiver can be obtained for a fleet vehicle only after an
inspection by EPD's Management Contractor determines that no
repairs to that vehicle can significantly reduce emissions. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) The administrative fee charged to fleet test stations
shall be at least the fee charged to public test stations. This
fee may be increased to cover any additional cost of increased
monitoring requirements for fleet test stations. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(c) For fleets engaged in commercial activity, utility service
or government service: <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>1. In addition to the required biennial inspection, each fleet
vehicle as part of the vehicle's regular maintenance shall pass
periodic emission inspections. These unofficial emission
inspections shall be conducted at least semi-annually. Results of
these unofficial inspections shall be retained in the vehicle's maintenance
log for inspection by EPD or the Management Contractor; and <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>2. Maintenance and repair technicians employed by the fleet
test operator shall complete a state-recognized repair technician
training course. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) Quality Assurance for Fleet Vehicles <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) Fleet test stations and mobile test stations shall be
audited on at least the frequency of public test stations. EPD or
the Management Contractor may require or conduct emission
inspections on randomly selected fleet or car dealer vehicles at
any time as an added assurance that the vehicles are meeting emission requirements. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) At fleet test stations or mobile test stations where
tested vehicles are not meeting emission requirements, EPD may
require the test station operator to install a video camera
surveillance system on the test system which shall observe all
official emission inspections. The video camera surveillance
system shall be operated and maintained in accordance with the
procedures established in the I/M Test Manual. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="CertofAut"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.10 Certificates of Authorization. Amended. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Inspection stations which are demonstrated to EPD to meet all
requirements of these rules and, as applicable, to have conducted
inspections properly and otherwise complied with the rules under Chapter
391-3-10 shall be awarded a Certificate of Authorization which
will allow the holder to operate an emission inspection station
or stations as described in its application. Certificates of Authorization
shall be valid for two years. Certificates may be suspended or revoked
at any time, after notice and offer of a hearing, for failure to
conduct inspections properly or to otherwise comply with these rules. </p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Inspecqul"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.11 Inspector Qualifications and Certification.
Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) In order to conduct emission inspections, inspectors must
complete an EPD-approved training program, pass a written and
hands-on test of efficiency and receive a certificate from EPD. Inspectors
shall also obtain training on the proper operation of inspection
equipment from the manufacturer of the test equipment which their
inspection station uses. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) The EPD-approved training program will include information
on: <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) Air pollution, its causes and effects; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) The purpose and functions of the State Inspection Program; <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(c) Inspection regulations and procedures, including technical
details and the rationale for their design; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(d) Emission control devices functions, configuration,
identification and inspection; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(e) Test equipment operation, calibration and maintenance; <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(f) Quality control procedures and their purpose; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(g) Public relations; and <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(h) Safety and health issues related to inspections. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) Inspectors must demonstrate knowledge and proficiency in
proper inspection procedures. Inspectors must pass (with 80%
correct answers) a written test on all aspects of the training. Inspectors
must also pass a hands-on test by demonstrating that they can
perform all parts of the inspection correctly. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) Inspectors who satisfactorily complete a training program
and pass the written and hands-on test will receive a certificate
from EPD. Certificates may be suspended or revoked at any time, after
notice and offer of a hearing, for failure to conduct inspections
properly or to otherwise comply with these rules. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(5) Certificates are valid for two years. Certificates may be
renewed upon completion of a refresher training program approved
by EPD. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Schedule"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.12 Schedules for Emission Tests. Amended. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) The inspection term shall be biennial. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) Even model year vehicles shall be tested in even test
years. Odd model year vehicles shall be tested in odd test years.
For the 1997 test year, odd model year vehicles may be tested at
any time during the test year prior to the vehicle's registration
date. For the 1998 test year, even model year vehicles may be
tested at any time during the test year prior to the vehicle
registration date. In subsequent years, vehicles shall be tested
within 90 days prior to the vehicle registration date in the required
years. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) All covered vehicles must have a current passing or waiver
Certificate of Emission Inspection to obtain a registration each
year. A valid Certificate from a regular inspection may be used
to obtain registration for that test year and the following year. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) Vehicles registered outside a covered county which are
purchased by a resident of a covered county must receive an
initial emission inspection prior to being registered in a
covered county. This inspection shall be performed within thirty
(30) days of the purchase of the vehicle. Anyone newly
establishing residence in a covered county shall have an
inspection performed on their vehicle(s) within thirty (30) days
of establishing residence in the covered county. During the
period of October 1, 1996, through December 31, 1996, inspections
of such newly registered vehicles are required only for 1985 and newer
vehicles required to be registered in Cobb, DeKalb, Fulton and Gwinnett
Counties. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(5) For vehicles which are tested under paragraph (4), if the
vehicle is tested in its regular inspection test year, the
inspection shall be valid for registration in the year it was
tested and the following year. If the vehicle is tested in an off-year, the
inspection shall be valid for registration only in the year of
testing, if the vehicle's registration date in the following year
is more than 12 months after the date of the inspection. If the
vehicle's registration date in the following year is less than 12
months after the date of inspection, the inspection shall be valid
for registration in the test year and the two following years.
For even model year vehicles which are tested prior to July 1, 1997,
the inspection shall be valid for the 1997 vehicle registration
year only. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Certi-13"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.13 Certificate of Emission Inspection. Amended. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Owners of vehicles which receive an emission inspection
shall receive a Certificate of Emission Inspection. The
Certificate shall be in a form provided by EPD. The Certificate
shall include: <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) The Vehicle Identification Number; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) The license plate number; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(c) The vehicle make and model year; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(d) The test date and time, location and inspector(s); <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(e) The test type (initial, retest); <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(f) The inspection fee; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(g) Vehicle odometer reading; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(h) Fuel type; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(i) The test results for the exhaust emission test,
evaporative emissions test, and on-board diagnostic check (where
applicable); <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(j) The applicable standards for each test; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(k) For the tampering inspection, whether the catalytic
convertor is correctly installed, is tampered or was not
originally equipped; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(l) The pass or fail status for each test, and for the
complete emission inspection; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(m) For vehicles which pass the complete emission inspection,
the year(s) of registration that are covered by that inspection; </p>

<p>(n) Information on the possible availability of warranty
repairs and information on repairs which may be useful in fixing
failed vehicles; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(o) A repair information section. This section shall include a
checklist of common repairs and spaces for the repair technician
to insert his or her name, the business name and address and the cost
of repairs; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(p) Any other information required by EPD. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) Station owners shall purchase Certificate forms from EPD
or the Management Contractor at a price established by EPD.
Alternatively, station owners will be supplied Certificate forms
in quantities adequate to perform inspections on vehicles for
which the test station has pre-paid the program administrative
fee. The method for fee collection and Certificate distribution shall be established
by the Director. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Sticker-14"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.14 Emission Inspection Sticker. Amended. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) For vehicles which pass the emission inspection, the
inspector shall affix a sticker to the bottom of the driver's
side of the vehicle's windshield. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) The sticker shall include: <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) The date assigned for the next test. The next test date
shall be visible from outside the vehicle and be in characters at
least one inch tall. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) A serial number. </p>

<p>(3) Stickers will be supplied by EPD or the Management
Contractor. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) The sticker shall remain affixed at all times and shall be
removed only upon replacement at the next scheduled test. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(5) Stickers shall be stored in a secure place. All missing
stickers shall be reported to EPD or the Management Contractor
immediately. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(6) Replacement stickers may be affixed by EPD or the
Management Contractor after verification that the vehicle has
passed its latest scheduled emission inspection. The fee for a
replacement sticker shall reflect the cost of providing the
replacement sticker. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Repairs-14"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.15 Repairs and Retests. Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Owners of vehicles which fail any portion of the emission
inspection shall have necessary maintenance and repairs
performed. Vehicles which are brought to an inspection station
operated by the same owner as the station which performed the
original inspection within 30 days of a test failure will be given
one reinspection at no additional charge. If any additional
reinspections are required to pass the inspection requirement,
another test fee shall be charged. This fee will cover one
reinspection and, if required, one additional reinspection. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) Owners of vehicles presented for reinspection shall
present a completed repair information form. No reinspection,
whether paid or unpaid, shall be performed unless the repair
information form has been completed. This information should be
completed by the repair facility which repaired the vehicle. This
information shall be entered into the inspection database by the station performing
the reinspection. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) Repair of failed vehicles by the owner or other persons
who are not recognized repair technicians is permitted; however,
the cost of such repairs, except repairs to primary emission control
components, shall not be counted toward a waiver for any 1980 or
later model vehicle. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) Except as noted, reinspections shall consist only of the
portions of the test which were failed in the initial inspection,
i.e., exhaust, gas cap, tampering, OBD. For an exhaust emission
reinspection, the vehicle must pass the inspection for all pollutants
(HC, CO, NO<sub>x</sub>). <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(5) Vehicles which pass the reinspection will receive a
passing Certificate and sticker. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Extension-16"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.16 Extensions, Reciprocal Tests. Amended. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Owners of vehicles which are temporarily stationed in a
location which is outside the covered counties, and which cannot
be easily brought to the covered counties for inspection may
request an extension of time to comply. The request for an
extension shall include proof that the owner is stationed outside
the covered counties, e.g., military orders, school registration
or other documentation acceptable to EPD. Extensions may be
granted for up to one year, but in no case will the extension
period extend beyond the end of the regular inspection test year. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) Vehicles which will be stationed outside the covered
counties past the end of the regular inspection test year must be
tested prior to leaving or must receive a reciprocal test.
Vehicles which will be stationed outside the covered counties may
be tested earlier than their regular inspection period if needed
to comply with this requirement. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) Vehicles stationed outside the covered counties may comply
with the inspection requirement by passing an emission inspection
from an inspection program which EPD and the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency have determined to be equivalent to the Georgia
program. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) Extensions may be granted by EPD or the Management
Contractor. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(5) Inspection stations may perform inspections for vehicles
which are licensed in areas outside of the covered counties in
order for vehicle owners to comply with inspection requirements
in other states. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Waivers-17"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.17 Waivers. Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Vehicles which fail a reinspection despite expenditures
over a set limit on appropriate repairs and which have met
certain other criteria may be granted a waiver from complying
with the inspection requirements for that test cycle. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) In order to obtain a waiver the following criteria must
have been met: <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(a) An expenditure of at least $450 must have been made on
qualifying repairs after the vehicle fails the initial test. The
$450 level will be adjusted each year to reflect the change in
the Consumer Price Index after 1989. EPD will establish this
level effective at the start of each test year. For vehicles
which otherwise qualify for waivers during the period of October
1, 1996 to December 31, 1997, the waiver limit shall be $200 of
qualifying repairs. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) Receipts for these expenditures shall be submitted by the
vehicle owner. Vehicle owners shall present the vehicle for which
the waiver is requested to an authorized waiver inspect on
facility for verification of waiver eligibility. This verification
shall include an inspection of the vehicle to confirm that
reported repairs have been performed and to assess possible
reasons for the vehicle's failure to meet the emission
requirements. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(c) Qualifying repairs do not include: <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>1. repair or replacement of tampered emission control
equipment, after December 31, 1998; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>2. for 1980 and later model vehicles, repairs performed by
persons other than a recognized repair technician, except for
repairs to primary emission control components; <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>3. repairs that are unrelated to emission performance or are
inappropriate for the type of test failure. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(d) Motorists must utilize emission performance warranty
coverage. If the vehicle is within the age and mileage
limitations of the federal Clean Air Act warranty provisions
contained in Section 207(b), the owner must present a written
denial of warranty coverage from the manufacturer or authorized dealer. </p>

<p>(e) Repairs shall have produced a reduction in emissions for
the tests and pollutants which were failed during the initial
test of the test year. Retest exhaust emission levels for
pollutants which originally passed shall not exceed the relevant standards. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(f) Waivers shall be issued by EPD or the Management
Contractor. Before issuing a waiver, the issuer shall verify that
receipts for qualifying repairs exceeding the established waiver
amount have been submitted and that the vehicle is otherwise
qualified to receive a waiver. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) Waivers are valid for one test cycle. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Sale-18"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.18 Sale of Vehicles. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Under the provisions of Section 12-9-54 of the Act, no
person in a covered county shall sell at retail any responsible
motor vehicle, as defined by the Act, intended for highway use
without a currently valid Certificate of Emission Inspection, or
without a valid emission sticker affixed, if the purchaser as provided
by law is to register subject vehicle in any covered county. Any
person violating this Section shall be guilty of a misdemeanor
and upon conviction thereof, shall be punished by a fine of $100
for a first offense, $500 for a second offense and $1000 for each subsequent
offense. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) The sale of a used motor vehicle with an emission sticker
affixed represents that the vehicle has met all requirements as
prescribed by Georgia laws and rules and regulations. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) A current emission inspection Certificate or sticker is
not required for any motor vehicle that might otherwise be
subject to pre-sale emission inspection, but is sold for salvage
or for parts rather than for use as a motor vehicle on the streets
and highways, provided that said vehicle is not in fact operated
on the streets and highways, but is towed or hauled by some other
vehicle. The purpose for which the vehicle is sold shall be
indicated by the seller on the bill of sale. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Management-19"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.19 Management Contractor. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Pursuant to the provisions of the Act (O.G.C.A. 12-9-46),
the Director, on behalf of the Board of Natural Resources, may
contract with any person as necessary to implement the state inspection
program. The Department may contract for the design and operation
of a centralized data system and other functions as determined by
the Director. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) The Management Contractor will be responsible for
designing and maintaining an inspection database that will
include all vehicles subject to inspection in the covered
counties. This database will include all inspection and other
information required by these rules or by the management contract. Access to
the information in this database shall be made available to EPD
for oversight, data analysis and other purposes, and to county
tag offices in the covered counties for the purpose of
determining compliance with the inspection requirement for
vehicles which are to be registered. Data in this database may not
be used for any other purpose unless specifically authorized by
the Director. EPD may set conditions for access to the database
to ensure confidentiality. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) The Management Contractor, and its employees, shall not be
engaged in, nor have any financial interest in, the repair of
motor vehicles, nor in the operation of any emission inspection station.
Financial interest in the repair of vehicles shall include the
ownership or operation of repair facilities or the sale of motor vehicles
or motor vehicle parts. </p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Referee-20"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.20 Referee Program. Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Should a vehicle owner question the test procedures,
inspection equipment accuracy or validity of inspection results,
the owner may request that a referee test be performed on the
vehicle. The owner must request the referee test within ten days
of the inspection in question. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) Referee tests shall be observed by EPD or the Management
Contractor at a mutually agreed upon time at the inspection
station where the test in question was performed. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) Prior to referee tests, EPD or the Management Contractor
will review all calibration records to ensure that the analyzer
and other equipment are meeting the appropriate specifications.
EPD or the Management Contractor will then observe the conduct of
a complete emission inspection by station personnel to ensure
that it is properly performed. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(4) If the vehicle passes the referee test, the vehicle will
be given a passing Certificate of Emission Inspection and an
Emission Inspection Sticker. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Fees-21"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-.21 Inspection Fees. Amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(1) Emission inspection fees shall be due from the owner when
the vehicle starts the inspection process. Vehicles which are
rejected prior to the start of the inspection process for failure
to have recall work performed or for being unsafe to test shall
not be charged a fee. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(2) The emission inspection fee shall consist of the cost of
program administration plus a fee paid to the inspection station
for the cost of performing the inspection. The fee shall be
established by the inspection station but shall be no less than
$10.00 and no more than $25.00. The fee shall be posted at each public
test station on the test station's State Inspection Program sign.
The fee will cover an initial inspection, plus one free reinspection.
A new fee will be charged for subsequent reinspections. Each reinspection
fee will cover one reinspection and, if required, one additional reinspection. <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(3) Program Administration Fees <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Each test station shall remit to the Department a program
administration fee of $7.40 for each inspection or reinspection
for which an emission inspection fee is paid. The Department
shall remit five dollars and forty-five cents ($5.45) of each paid
fee to the Management Contractor for providing program management services
associated with implementation of the program. The Department
shall remit one dollar ($1.00) of each paid fee to the
appropriate county governing authority for each responsible motor
vehicle that is registered in that county. Ninety-five cents ($0.95)
of each paid fee shall be remitted to the Department to cover the
costs of providing oversight and other services needed for the implementation
of the program. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>(b) Each fleet test station where EPD has required the
installation and operation of a video camera surveillance system
shall remit to the Department a program administration fee of
$8.40 for each inspection or reinspection for which an emission
inspection fee is paid. The Department shall remit five dollars
and forty-five cents ($5.45) of each paid fee to the Management Contractor
for providing program management services associated with implementation
of the program. The Department shall remit one dollar ($1.00) of
each paid fee to the appropriate county governing authority for
each responsible motor vehicle that is registered in that county.
One dollar and ninety-five cents ($1.95) of each paid fee shall
be remitted to the Department to cover the costs of providing
oversight and other services needed for the implementation of the
program. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<a name="Enforcement-22"></a> </p>

<p>391-3-20-0.32-.22 Enforcement. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>The administration and enforcement of these rules and
regulations shall be as prescribed in the Act (O.C.G.A. Section
12-9-40, et seq., as amended) and in compliance with the minimum
applicable requirements as prescribed by the Georgia
Administrative Procedures Act (O.C.G.A. Section 50-13-1, et seq., as amended). <br
wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>

<p>Authority, O.C.G.A. 12-9-40, et seq., as amended. <br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1">
<br wp="br2">
</p>
