<title>EPD ADDRESSES THREAT OF WATERBORNE DISEASE</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
</head>

<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF" stylesrc="index.htm">

<p align="center"><img src="images/EPDMAST.GIF" align="bottom"
width="612" height="216"><br>
<a href="epd001.htm">[First Article]</a><a href="epd001.htm">[Previous
Article]</a><a href="epd003.htm">[Next Article]</a><a
href="epd015.htm">[Last Article]</a><a href="epd000.htm">[Index]</a><a
href="epd016.htm">[About]</a></p>

<h3>EPD ADDRESSES THREAT OF WATERBORNE DISEASE</h3>

<p>EPD has developed a strategy to address the threat of
cryptosporidiosis and other waterborne disease outbreaks in
Georgia's water systems. The plan has four areas of emphasis:
prevention; monitoring and surveillance; public education; and
response. It was developed with input from CDC, EPA, American
Water Works Association, water utilities and the Georgia Dept. of
Human Resources. <br>
The monitoring will include compliance with the Federal
Information Collection Rule (ICR), issued in May, which requires
large surface-water systems serving more than 100,000 people to
test their raw and/or treated water for the presence of Giardia,
cryptosporidium, viruses, and several disinfectant products. The
data will support amendments to regulations for surface water
treatment and future regulations for disinfectants and
disinfection by-products. Twelve public water systems, which
serve more than 4.3 million Georgians, must comply with this
monitoring requirement: Albany, Atlanta, Fulton County, Augusta,
Clayton County, Cobb County-Marietta, Columbus, Dekalb County,
Gwinnett County, Macon, Savannah and Warner Robins. EPD's
Drinking Water Laboratory will offer laboratory services and
technical assistance to these systems without an increasein their
current fees for testing services.<br>
For more information, contact the Drinking Water Program at (404)
656-5660.</p>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
