<head>
<title>New Rules</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
</head>

<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF" stylesrc="index.htm">

<p align="center"><img src="images/EPDMAST.GIF" align="bottom"
width="612" height="216"><br>
<a href="epd001.htm">[First Article]</a><a href="epd002.htm">[Previous
Article]</a><a href="epd004.htm">[Next Article]</a><a
href="epd015.htm">[Last Article]</a><a href="epd000.htm">[Index]</a><a
href="epd016.htm">[About]</a></p>

<h3><u>New Rules</u></h3>

<h3>Underground Storage Tank Management</h3>

<p>In April, the DNR Board adopted proposed amendments to the
Rules for Underground Storage Tank (UST) Management, Chapter
391-3-15, with the exception of the rule regarding an increase in
the Environmental Assurance Fees. Approved amendments include
reference to the 1995 Code of Federal Regulations (rather than
the 1993 version) and incorporate the U.S. EPA UST Lender
Liability Rules. EPD had proposed a 0.3 cent per gallon increase
in the Environmental Assurance Fee from 0.2 cents per gallon to
0.5 cents per gallon. In response to public comment, the Board
asked EPD to evaluate the availability of private environmental
insurance for owners of UST's. EPD reported in June that private
insurance was not readily available and recommended increasing
the fee to replenish the trust fund. A public hearing on a rule
proposed to increase the fee is scheduled for August 5.</p>

<h3>Petroleum Pipeline Eminent Domain Permit Procedures</h3>

<p>At the June meeting, the DNR Board adopted proposed Rules for
Petroleum Pipeline Eminent Domain Permit Procedures. The rules
were drafted by a task force that included representatives of
EPD, the Department of Transportation, and local government,
industry, and environmental interests. The rules (1) provide
protection to landowners for damages associated with pipeline
surveys; (2) define conditions under which petroleum pipeline
companies may use condemnation (requiring reasonable notification
to the landowner); and<br>
(3) outline permit application requirements and permit issuance
procedures to be followed prior to condemnation. </p>

<h3>Air Quality</h3>

<p>At the May meeting, the Board adopted proposed amendments to
Georgia's Rules for Air Quality Control, Chapter 391-3-1;
Georgia's Rules for Inspection and Maintenance, Chapter 391-3-10;
Georgia's Rules for Asbestos Removal and Encapsulation, Chapter
391-3-14; and emergency amendments to Georgia's Rules for
Enhanced Inspection and Maintenance, Chapter 391-3-20. <br>
The amendments to the Rules for Air Quality Control adopt, by
reference, the updated federal rules relating to Prevention of
Significant Deterioration, New Source Performance Standards, and
Emission Standards for Hazardous Air Pollutants. In addition, the
changes update the definition of volatile organic compound to
exempt perchloroethylene, add a definition for hazardous air
pollutant, clarify exemptions to permitting, update the permit
fee rule and manual for calculating 1995 fees, establish a list
of insignificant activities for Title V operating permits, and
establish a permit by rule for peanut/nut shelling and gluing
operations. <br>
The amendments to the Rules for Asbestos Removal and
Encapsulation reflect changes in the Asbestos Safety Act enacted
during the 1996 General Assembly. The Rules (1) abolish the
Asbestos Licensing Board; and (2)reestablish requirements for
contractor licensing, asbestos supervisor training and
administration of enforcement under the authority of the DNR
Board and the Director of EPD. <br>
Amendments to the Rules for Vehicle Inspection and Maintenance
delay the termination of the existing basic inspection and
maintenance program in Cobb, DeKalb, Fulton, and Gwinnett
Counties from June 30, 1996 until September 30, 1996. The rule
also extends current Certificates of Authorization to operate
inspection stations to September 30. The existing program was
extended for three months to allow additional time to implement
the enhanced inspection and maintenance program, which will
replace the existing program.<br>
EPD withdrew from consideration the proposed amendments to the
Rules for Enhanced Inspection and Maintenance (391-3-20)
originally scheduled for consideration at the May 29 Board
meeting and offered an emergency amendment. Delay in procurement
of a contractor to design and manage the testing program delayed
the start date for the new program, as well as development of
equipment specifications and a fee structure. Emergency
amendments to the Rules were necessary to avoid further delays in
implementing the program. The Board adopted emergency amendments
which delay start of the enhanced program from July 1, 1996 to
October 1, 1996 and make various technical revisions:
definitions, test station requirements, on-road testing, waivers
(reducing the repair waiver from $450 to $200 until December 30,
1996), test procedures equipment specifications and fee
structure. (Emergency rules remain in effect for a maximum of 120
days; a public hearing on the rules will be held on August 13,
and consideration for regular adoption by the Board is
tentatively scheduled for August 23). </p>

<h3>Lead Based Paint Abatement and Certification</h3>

<p>Proposed Rules for Lead-Based Paint Abatement and
Certification were adopted at the June 26 Board meeting. These
rules provide for accreditation of training programs,
certification of individuals and and firms engaged in lead-based
paint activities, and establish standards for performing those
activities. The rules are applicable to all individuals and firms
engaged in lead-based paint activities, except persons who
perform these activities within residential dwellings that they
own and which are occupied by the owner or the owner's immediate
family. The abatement of lead-based paint is not required by
these rules.</p>

<h3>Water Quality</h3>

<p>In April, the Board adopted emergency rules to ensure EPD's
authority in implementing the NPDES permit program. This action
stemmed from a February 20, 1996 Fulton County Superior Court
ruling by Judge Alice Bonner that the Board of Natural Resources
is not authorized to adopt rules and regulations to implement the
Georgia Water Quality Control Act. Governor Miller has since
signed HB 1788 to grant the Board this authority under the
Georgia Water Quality Control Act. The emergency amendment
adopted the existing Rules and Regulations for Water Quality
Control in its entirety except for three subparagraphs. These
three revisions were necessary due to Judge Bonner's ruling and
included deletion of the section on General Permit for
Construction Activities and a clarification of the conditions
under which general NPDES permits will be issued. <br>
Emergency rules remain in effect for a maximum of 120 days during
which public input must be solicited before the rules are
presented to the Board for regular adoption. A public hearing was
held on May 23, 1996 to receive comments on the emergency rules
adopted at the April meeting, with several modifications. The
modifications were proposed to make the rules conform with U.S.
EPA guidance and/or requirements (water quality standard for
arsenic, sewage sludge requirements for chromium, molybdenum, and
selenium, various signatory requirements for documents). The
rules, including modifications, were adopted by the Board at its
June 26 meeting. <br>
</p>

<hr>

<h3>COPIES OF ALL EPD RULES ARE AVAILABLE FROM EPD'S CUSTOMER
ASSISTANCE PROGRAM (404) 656-4713.</h3>
</body>
