<title>Legal Matters</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
</head>

<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF" stylesrc="index.htm">

<p align="center"><img src="images/EPDMAST.GIF" align="bottom"
width="612" height="216"><br>
<a href="epd001.htm">[First Article]</a><a href="epd005.htm">[Previous
Article]</a><a href="epd007.htm">[Next Article]</a><a
href="epd015.htm">[Last Article]</a><a href="epd000.htm">[Index]</a><a
href="epd016.htm">[About]</a></p>

<h3 align="left">Legal Matters</h3>

<ul>
    <li>On March 5, 1996, Administrative Law Judge (ALJ) Mark
        Dickerson denied a petition filed by Scripto-Tokai to
        halt EPD cleanup activities (OSAH-DNR-EPD-HSR-AH 1-96).
        Scripto-Tokai and EPD entered into a consent order under
        the Hazardous Site Response Act (HSRA) requiring Scripto
        to remediate past releases of hazardous waste. Since
        Scripto did not proceed with remediation, EPD proceeded
        with its own clean-up. Scripto filed a petition for
        administrative review which sought enforcement of a stay
        of EPD's activities (administrative rules provide for an
        automatic stay of any order or action of EPD after a
        petition has been filed). Citing restrictions contained
        in O.C.G.A. 12-2-2(c)(3)(B) on administrative review of
        orders issued under HSRA, Judge Dickerson ruled that
        EPD's activities were not reviewable unless the agency
        attempted to enforce the order or recover costs. <br>
    </li>
    <li>In a Final Decision on April 9, 1996, ALJ Mark Dickerson
        granted the EPD Director's motion to dismiss an appeal
        filed by J. P. Stevens &amp; Company (OSAH-DNR-EPD-HSR-AH
        1-95). Stevens, the former owner of a textile
        manufacturing facility in East Dublin had been identified
        by the Director as a responsible party for the release of
        solvents which have contaminated groundwater on the
        property. Pursuant to O.C.G.A. ¤ 12-8-97(a)(8), the
        Director issued a letter on July 14, 1995 designating the
        sites as needing corrective action. Such a designation
        triggers the deed and deed record requirements of
        O.C.G.A. ¤ 12-8-97(b) and (c) and is an action subject
        to administrative appeal. In granting the motion to
        dismiss, Judge Dickerson concluded that Stevens failed to
        demonstrate that any harm would result from the
        Director's letter. The ALJ noted that any corrective
        actions that EPD might take or require Stevens to take
        would also not be reviewable until EPD attempted to
        enforce the requirements or to recover costs. <br>
        The Georgia Hazardous Sites Response Act is unique in its
        exemption of certain actions and orders of the Director
        from administrative review. The purpose of this exemption
        is to enable the Director to promptly respond to serious
        environmental threats posed by the release of hazardous
        substances. The ruling does not impact responsible
        parties' rights for administrative review should the
        Director seek to recover response costs, enforce an order
        or recover a penalty for violation of an order.<br>
    </li>
    <li>On May 28, 1996, ALJ Mark Dickerson affirmed EPD's denial
        of a solid waste handling permit for a proposed landfill
        in Long County (OSAH-DNR-EPD-SW-AH 6-95). The landfill
        site, proposed by GSW, Inc., is located within a Special
        Use Airspace designated for Department of Defense
        Townsend Bombing Range use. Judge Dickerson ruled that
        construction and operation of the proposed landfill will
        likely attract birds to the site which will increase
        their numbers and create a hazard for aircraft utilizing
        the Townsend Bombing Range. Consequently, the proposed
        landfill would violate DNR Rule 391-3-4-.04(1) in
        creating a hazard to the health, safety, and well-being
        of both aircraft occupants and persons in the vicinity of
        the proposed site. <br>
    </li>
    <li>On June 26, 1996, ALJ Mark Dickerson affirmed the
        Director's entry of Consent Order No. EPD-WQ-1963,
        Amendment 2 (OSAH-DNR-EPD-WQ 11-95). <br>
        The 1992 NPDES permit issued for the City of Cornelia's
        WPCP significantly decreased previous ammonia effluent
        limits; an Administrative Order issued simultaneously
        established the effective date of the more stringent
        limits as June 30, 1995. When a major industrial user
        (Fieldale Farms), failed to comply with its 1991 Consent
        Order to reduce ammonia pretreatment effluent
        concentrations, the Director entered into a Consent
        Agreement with Cornelia, extending the compliancedate for
        meeting ammonia limits at the City's facility to May 30,
        1996.<br>
        The Upper Chattahoochee Riverkeeper Fund, Inc. petitioned
        for an administrative review, seeking reversal of the
        Consent Order on allegations that it was both
        unauthorized and unreasonable. Challenges to the
        Director's authority to issue the 1995 Consent Order were
        resolved against the Riverkeeper in March, 1996 (in an
        Order on Riverkeeper's motion for summary determination). <br>
        The challenge to reasonableness of the Consent Order
        remained, and was the subject of a hearing held in April,
        1996. In his final decision, Judge Dickerson concluded
        that (1) the Director has specific authority to issue an
        order which includes a schedule of compliance where a
        facility is unable to achieve the limitations contained
        in its permit when the permit issued; and (2) the
        Riverkeeper failed to prove that the 1995 Consent Order
        was not a reasonable exercise of the Director's
        authority. The decision noted that &quot;reasonable does
        not mean perfect or even that the Director's choice is
        the choice that other reasonable persons might choose.
        Reasonable also does not mean, when viewed after the
        fact, successful. It just means that the Director made an
        enforcement choice that was among those within his
        authority and among those a reasonable person might
        choose.&quot;<br>
        Judge Dickerson also declined to fashion a &quot;more
        reasonable order&quot;, as suggested in post-hearing
        filings by the Riverkeeper, noting that so long as the
        Director exercises his authority in a lawful and
        reasonable manner, an ALJ has no authority to substitute
        the ALJ's judgment for the Director's judgment as to what
        the ALJ thinks might have been a better enforcement
        choice.</li>
</ul>
</body>
</html>
