href="epd015.htm">[Last Article]</a><a href="epd000.htm">[Index]</a><a
href="epd016.htm">[About]</a></p>

<h3>EPD RELEASES 1994 TOXIC INVENTORY REPORT</h3>

<p>The 1994 Toxic Release Inventory (TRI) report has been
completed. The total number of pounds of toxic chemicals released
in Georgia increased by three percent in 1994. Most of the
increase can be attributed to increased stack emissions reported
by 18 facilities. The higher numbers at these industries were
associated with higher production levels and revised reporting
requirements. The five counties with the largest amounts of toxic
chemicals released were, from largest to smallest: Chatham,
Richmond, Early, Fulton, and Glynn. The top 10 chemicals released
were: methanol, ammonia, toluene, xylene, hydrochloric acid,
methyl ethyl ketone, dichloromethane, glycol ethers, ammonium
nitrate,<br>
and styrene.<br>
Despite the increase in total pounds of chemicals released, the
overall toxicity of releases in Georgia decreased. A toxicity
index which reflects both the amount released and the danger
presented for 27 chemicals showed a decrease of 50% when compared<br>
to the same index for last year. This decrease resulted from
voluntary reductions of emissions of chloroform<br>
by pulp and paper mills and of trichloroethylene by aircraft
manufacturers.<br>
For additional information, or to request a copy of the report,
contact Dr. Bert Langley of EPD's Community Right-to-Know Program
at (404) 656-6905.<br>
</p>
</body>
</html>
