href="epd016.htm">[About]</a></p>

<h3>TWO BRANCHES REORGANIZE</h3>

<p>The Water Protection and Land Protection Branches have
reorganized to address current and future customer needs more
efficiently. <br>
The new Water Protection Branch structure allows for increased
emphasis on management of entire watersheds and control of
non-point sources of pollution. The reorganization consolidated
the industrial and municipal permitting, compliance, and
enforcement functions into the Permitting Compliance and
Enforcement Program (Tradeport office complex; 404/ 362-2680;
Jeff Larson, Prog. Mgr). A NonPoint Source Program has been
formed to handle regulatory functions including erosion and
sedimentation, stormwater from industrial, municipal and
construction activities, and section 319 grant functions dealing
with non-point sources of pollution (Suite 1070 East Floyd Tower;
404/656-4887; Larry Hedges, Prog. Mgr). Field monitoring,
compliance sampling, aquatic biomonitoring, intensive surveys and
ambient monitoring functions have been combined into the
Watershed Planning and Monitoring Program ( 7 MLK; 404/ 656-4905;
Mork Winn, Prog. Mgr.). Most functions of the Municipal
Engineering Program are unchanged, though the program will now be
known as Engineering and Technical Support (Suite 1052, East
Floyd Tower; 404/656-4708; Pete Maye, Prog. Mgr). <br>
Lewis Tinley has assumed the duties of Assistant Chief of the
Land Protection Branch. The Municipal Solid Waste and the
Commercial/Industrial Solid Waste Programs have been combined to
form the Solid Waste Management Program (404/ 362-2692; Jim
Dunbar, Prog. Mgr). Regulatory programs for lead and asbestos
abatement will be administered by Land Protection (404) 362-2537;
asbestos was previously regulated by the Air Protection Branch.<br>
</p>
</body>
