<p align="center"><img src="images/EPDMAST.GIF" align="bottom"
width="612" height="216"><br>
<a href="epd001.htm">[First Article]</a><a href="epd010.htm">[Previous
Article]</a><a href="epd012.htm">[Next Article]</a><a
href="epd016.htm">[Last Article]</a><a href="epd000.htm">[Index]</a><a
href="epd016.htm">[About]</a></p>

<h3>GRANTS AVAILABLE TO LOCAL GOVERNMENTS</h3>

<p>Grants for local governments to clean up scrap tire piles
within their jurisdictions and/or implement scrap tire
enforcement and education programs will be funded from the Solid
Waste Trust Fund again this state fiscal year. The Scrap Tire
Pile Clean-Up Program funds-on an actual cost basis - the clean
up of scrap tire piles containing more than 5,000 tires, tire
removals from roadside clean-ups and/or scrap tire recycle
projects. EPD Contact: Denny Jackson (404) 362-2696. The
Enforcement grants (maximum $50,000; 25% local match required)
are awarded to implement local solid waste regulatory programs to
prevent scrap tire dumping, develop tire enforcement ordinances,
and/ or hire code enforcement officers. Education grants up to
$25,000 are available for educational efforts to promote waste
reduction, recycling, and recycling market development; a 25%
local match is required. EPD Contact: Kristi Campbell (404)
362-2587. <br>
The 1996 General Assembly appropriated $2.7 million to provide
grants to local governments in the Chattahoochee River Basin to
deal with downstream environmental problems. The grants will
range from $10,000 to $1,000,000. Eligible recipients are local
and regional governments and authorities located in the
Chattahoochee River Basin downstream of Atlanta. The grants will
be used for water quality monitoring, to implement projects that
mitigate documented water quality problems in the Chattahoochee
River, to provide public education on Chattahoochee water quality
issues, to develop and/or implement non-point source management
strategies, or to mitigate documented water treatment problems.
Deadline for applications: September 1. Grant awards will be
announced in October. EPD Contact: Pete Maye (404) 656-4708.<br>
</p>
</body>
</html>
