content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Air Protection Branch Description</title>
</head>

<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<h1 align="center"><b>AIR PROTECTION BRANCH</b> </h1>

<h3 align="center"><b>Ronald C. Methier, Chief</b> <br>
<b>4244 International Parkway, Suite 120</b> <br>
<b>Atlanta, Georgia 30354</b> <br>
404/<b>363-7000</b> </h3>

<p>The Air Protection Branch has the responsibility of
administering the ambient (outside) air quality rules and
regulations (both state and federal) for the State of Georgia. </p>

<h3><b>AMBIENT MONITORING PROGRAM</b> </h3>

<address>
    <b>Rafael A. Ballagas, Program Manager</b> <br>
    <b>404/363-7006</b> 
</address>

<p>The Ambient Monitoring Program (AMP) measures levels of air
pollutants throughout the State. The data is used to determine
compliance with air standards established for six compounds and
to evaluate the need for any special controls for various other
pollutants. Measurements of the following are collected: ozone
(O3), sulfur dioxide (SO2), carbon monoxide (CO), nitrogen dioxide
(NO2), particulate matter (PM10), acid rain, organic compounds
related to ozone formation, and toxics. </p>

<h3><b>INDUSTRIAL SOURCE MONITORING PROGRAM</b> </h3>

<address>
    <b>Mike Fogle, Program Manager</b> <br>
    <b>404/363-7141</b> 
</address>

<p>The Industrial Source Monitoring Program is responsible for
specifying and approving all stationary source emissions
monitoring and testing procedures used by industry to meet the requirements
of any Federal and State regulations. It consists of the Chemical
and VOC Monitoring Unit and the Combustion and Mineral Products
Monitoring Unit. Personnel in the Program work closely with the
Stationary Source Compliance Program and the Stationary Source Permitting
Program in both permitting and enforcement matters to ensure that
consistent and reliable methods are always used by industry and
that the measurement of the emissions levels is reliable and
timely. </p>

<h3><b>MOBILE &amp; AREA SOURCES PROGRAM</b> </h3>

<address>
    <b>Marlin Gottschalk, Program Manager</b> <br>
    <b>404/363-7024</b> 
</address>

<p>This Program has responsibility for evaluation and control of
vehicle emissions and several smaller emission sources (primarily
around Atlanta). Emission sources and activities covered by this Program
are: gasoline vapor recovery (gasoline stations) and vehicle
emission testing (I&amp;M program). </p>

<h3><b>PLANNING &amp; SUPPORT PROGRAM</b> </h3>

<address>
    <b>Marvin M. Lowry, Program Manager</b> <br>
    <b>404/363-7014</b> 
</address>

<p>This Program has overall responsibility for air quality
modeling, quality assurance of air quality measurements, emission
inventories, permit fees; data storage systems and various
technical support functions. These would include: air quality
modeling for permits and control strategies, data systems
maintenance, quality assurance of statewide air monitoring
network data, preparation of information for Air Branch budget
and federal grants, tracking permit fee collections, and maintaining
and developing computer data systems for the Air Branch. The
Small Business Assistance Program is located in the Program and
the Program Manager serves as the State's Small Business
Ombudsman.</p>

<h3><b>STATIONARY SOURCE COMPLIANCE PROGRAM</b> </h3>

<address>
    <b>Edward (Tony) A. Cutrer, Program Manager</b> <br>
    <b>404/363-7115</b> 
</address>

<p>This Program has overall responsibility for conducting source
(company) inspections, enforcement of Air Quality Control Rules
on all combustion, chemical and mineral sources and all sources whose
principal emissions are volatile organic compounds (VOC's).
Facilities and/or items covered by this Program include:
automobile assembly plants, boilers, Georgia Power plants, incinerators,
medical waste incinerators, paint booths, printers, textile
plants, cement plants, pulp &amp; paper mills, quarries, asphalt
plants, kaolin &amp; fuller's earth plants, chemical plants,
fertilizer plants, acid plants, roofing plants, glass &amp;
fiberglass plants and battery plants. </p>

<h3><b>STATIONARY SOURCE PERMITTING PROGRAM</b> </h3>

<address>
    <b>Jack Taylor, Program Manager</b> <br>
    <b>404/363-7020</b> 
</address>

<p>The Stationary Source Permitting Program is designed to allow
the Air Branch to implement all air quality related permitting
requirements, including New Source Review (Major and Minor) programs
and all Operating Permit Programs, SIP, Synthetic Minor, Minor
and Title V. The SIP Operating Permit Program has been structured
to yield permits that will be considered federally enforceable
for limiting potential emissions and thus avoiding PSD and Title
V. The Permitting Program also has the responsibility for
implementing the Air Toxics permit program including 112(g)
modifications that need to be permitted. The Permitting Program
has the responsibility of permitting program development. Further
rule development on the state's Permit-by-Rule and FESOP
(federally enforceable operating permit) program is done by the
permitting program. The Permitting Program consists of four
units. </p>
</body>
</html>
