<html>

<head>
<title>Land Protection Branch Description</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1 align=center><b>LAND PROTECTION BRANCH</b> </h1>
<p align=center><b>4244 International Parkway, Suite 104</b> <br>
<b>Atlanta, Georgia 30354</b> <br>
<b>(404) 362-2537</b> </p>
<hr>
<p>The Land Protection Branch encompassed a wide diversity of Programs dealing with waste management activities or programs 
designed to prevent the release of materials into the environment, which when released may cause environmental damage, risk 
to public health or the depletion of non renewable natural resources. Programs in the Branch include the following. </p>
<h3><b>Solid Waste Management Program</b> </h3>
<p>The Solid Waste Management Program is responsible for regulating 467 solid waste handling facilities to ensure such facilities 
do not adversely affect to public health, safety and the environment and to encourage the reduction, reuse, and recycling of the 
resources in solid waste when feasible. Solid waste handling facilities include landfills, incinerators, materials recovery facilities, 
transfer stations, compost facilities, and land application facilities. Activities include permitting of landfills and other handling 
facilities, closure and post-closure care of existing landfills, financial assurance, groundwater, surface water and methane gas 
monitoring, and inspection of site operations. Through compliance inspections, the program insures that all operating solid 
waste handling facilities and landfills in closure or post-closure care status are in compliance with the requirements of the 
Georgia Comprehensive Solid Waste Management Act and the Rules of Solid Waste Management and that potential releases 
to the environment are prevented or where releases have occurred, corrective action is taken to return the facilities to 
compliance. </p>
<p>The Act requires the cooperation of a team of State agencies. The Department of Natural Resources has two divisions active 
in solid waste management. In addition to the enforcement and compliance activities previously mentioned, the Environmental 
Protection Division (EPD) of DNR provides technical support to local governments, the regulated community and the general 
public. Integrated solid waste management is stressed and use of new technology such as co-composting is encouraged. The 
program is responsible for assisting local communities with planning assessment, code development, solid waste enforcement 
programs, and evaluation of grant funding. The Pollution Prevention Assistance Division (P2AD) of DNR offers waste 
reduction technical assistance to business and industry, agriculture, governments, and the general public. The Department of 
Community Affairs (DCA) provides technical assistance to local governments in solid waste management, recycling, and waste 
reduction; reviews and approves local government solid waste management plans; educates the public; and provides an annual 
report on the status of solid waste management in Georgia. The Georgia Environmental Facilities Authority (GEFA) is a 
conduit through which the State provides solid waste related financial assistance to local governments. GEFA oversees several 
grant and loan programs that may be utilized by local governments for solid waste reduction efforts. All of the above agencies, 
together with local governments, private businesses and the general public, are working together to update the State solid 
waste management plan. EPD provides the overall coordination of statewide solid waste management activities. </p>
<p>In FY 1995, a total of 9,653,373 tons of solid waste were disposed in 136 permitted landfills in Georgia. A major emphasis of 
the program is the reduction of waste being disposed or if disposed, such disposal is in lined rather than unlined landfills. The 
Act sets a deadline of July, 1998 for all unlined landfills that received approval to vertically expand to cease receiving waste. 
All horizontal expansion must be lined as well. </p>
<p>Both operational as well as closed landfills are closely monitored to insure groundwater and other resources are not adversely 
impacted. </p>
<h3><b>Scrap Tire Program</b> </h3>
<p>There are approximately 6-7 million scrap tires generated annually in Georgia. In the past, many of these were improperly 
discarded. </p>
<p>The Scrap Tire Management Program is responsible for preventing the creation of new scrap tire piles and cleaning-up the 
existing tire piles around the State. The program regulates tire carriers, generators, retailers and processors of tires. A $1.00 
management fee is collected on the retail sale of new replacement tires. These fees are utilized for the clean-up of the scrap tire 
piles through the use of scrap tire abatement contractors or clean-up grants to local governments. The program also provides 
grants to local governments for develop solid waste enforcement program and for scrap tire/solid waste education programs. </p>
<p>In excess of 10.5 millions scrap tires/year are now being recycled by EPD approved facilities in Georgia. Most tires are being 
shredded into chips and used as supplement fuel by the paper mill industry and used as substitute gravel in septic tank drain 
lines, and various civil engineering projects. Tires are also being utilized in making other products such as bush hog wheels, 
dock bumpers, and landscaping mulch. A developing industry is the use of crumb rubber in the construction of rubber-asphalt 
highway construction projects, carpet manufacturing, rubber molded products and co-blending with plastics. </p>
<p>The Program has identified over 243 tire dumps throughout the state, encompassing over 5 million tires. Seventy four (74) of 
those sites, which included over 3 million tires, have been cleaned up through State Abatement Contractors and 
reimbursements to local governments. Efforts include the identification of all sites and their clean-up prior to the program 
statutory sunset in 2000. More sites are being found and the program continues to receive requests for abatement assistance 
from local governments, particularly for the clean-up of numerous smaller tire piles. These clean-ups are funded in conjunction 
with Enforcement and Education Grants to help these cities and counties hire an enforcement officer to inspect local tire 
dealers, generators, carriers, and processors and assure they are properly managing their scrap tires. The grants also allow 
them to educate their citizens about how and where to properly dispose of old tires, as well as the potential uses of and 
products made from recycled tires. To date, over a million dollars has been granted to 21 local governments for enforcement 
and education. As the larger site abatement program winds down, increased funding and emphasis will be shifted to local 
enforcement, education and other programs to prevent illegal tire dumping at the local level. </p>
<h3><b>Lead-Based Paint/Asbestos Abatement Program</b> </h3>
<p>The purpose of the program is to prevent lead-poisoning in occupants and workers of housing where abatement of lead-based 
paint is occurring, specifically children under the age of six. The Lead-Based Paint Abatement Certification Program 
implements regulations governing the training and certification of individuals, the accreditation of training providers, work 
standards, and enforcement. Lead poisoning can cause central nervous system disabilities, slower mental development, and 
other related problems. Improper lead-based paint abatement constitutes a serious threat to persons residing on or otherwise 
using an affected structure or site, to those performing such work, to the environment, and to the general public. </p>
<p>The Asbestos Program also requires licensing of contractors and training for asbestos supervisors. It insures the safe removal 
or encapsulation of friable asbestos-containing materials from facilities and residential dwellings in the safest manner possible. </p>
<p>Both the Lead and Asbestos Programs are fully funded by fees charged to certified trainers, individuals and workers, as well 
as fees on each abatement project. Project notification is required in order to select a small percentage of projects for 
compliance audits. In addition, all complaints are investigated to determine compliance with applicable standards. </p>
<h3><b>Surface Mining Program</b> </h3>
<p>The Surface Mining Program is responsible for protecting the environment, natural resources and citizens of Georgia from the 
adverse affects of surface mining. The removal of vegetation, soils and other changes which accompany surface mining 
operations could potentially result in adverse affects such as accelerated erosion, sterile soils, and sedimentation in surface 
waters. Regulatory activities include the issuing of surface mining permits to qualified applicants, conducting periodic on-site 
inspections of approximately 560 operations and conducting final on-site inspections to ascertain compliance with reclamation 
plans. Mining operations include kaolin, crushed stone, borrow pits, in-stream dredging, etc. The program is empowered to 
deny or revoke permits, issue consent orders, initiate court actions, and/or forfeit funds to conduct reclamation. </p>
<p>Reclamation is assured through the posting, with EPD, of up to $2,500/acre for mined lands. Should the required reclamation 
not be performed by the permit holder, EPD can require forfeiture of the bond and utilize such funds to contract directly for 
reclamation. </p>
<h3><b>Underground Storage Tank Management Program (USTMP)</b> </h3>
<p>The Underground Storage Tank Management Program is responsible for regulating approximately 49,000 underground 
storage tanks (USTs) at over 19,000 facilities in the state of Georgia to ensure such tanks do not leak petroleum or toxic 
chemicals into the environmental and, if leaks do occur, that the leaks are cleaned up. This Program is authorized by the 
Georgia Underground Storage tank Act, O.C.G.A. 12-13-1 and the Rules for Underground Storage Tank Management, 
Chapter 391-3-15. Activities of this Program fall into three major categories; (1) Regulatory Compliance, (2) Corrective 
Action, and (3) the Underground Storage Tank Trust Fund Administration. </p>
<h3><b>USTMP - Regulatory Compliance</b> </h3>
<p>This function is aimed at preventing future petroleum and chemical releases. By December 22, 1998, all of the approximately 
49,000 regulated USTs in Georgia must comply with certain spill, overfill, and corrosion protection requirements. All &#147;new&#148; 
USTs (those installed after December 22, 1988) must meet these requirements at the time of installation, while the owners 
and/or operators of all &#147;existing&#148; USTs (those installed before December 22, 1988) are faced with taking one of the three 
following actions to comply with this deadline: (1) Add spill, overfill, and corrosion protection; (2) close the UST system by 
December 22, 1998; or (3) replace each closed existing UST with a new UST. </p>
<p>Of particular concern are the 18,500 existing unprotected (bare) steel tanks with associated piping which must meet the 
corrosion protection requirements by upgrading with one of three methods: (1) adding cathodic protection; (2) adding interior 
lining; or (3) adding cathodic protection and interior lining. </p>
<h3><b>USTMP - Corrective Action</b> </h3>
<p>Where releases have occurred or cannot be prevented, corrective action is required. Over 6,000 releases (leaks) from USTs 
have been reported in Georgia since 1988. Once notified of a release, the owner/operator (O/O) is required to immediately 
repair the leak and submit reports detailing the extent of contamination from the leak and the physical conditions of the site. 
Based on information in these reports, a determination is made regarding the need for corrective action, and if needed, what 
type of corrective action would be most appropriate. If corrective action is required, the O/O must submit a corrective action 
plan (CAP) that outlines how the contamination will be cleaned up. The CAP is reviewed and approved prior to remediation 
efforts. Inspections of the site are conducted to ensure cleanup efforts are in accordance with the approved plan. </p>
<p>If an O/O fails to clean up a contaminated site, an order may be issued requiring that corrective action be taken within a 
prescribed time frame. If the O/O fails to comply with the order, civil penalties up to $25,000 for each day of continued 
noncompliance may be imposed. </p>
<p>The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency also provides funds to Georgia from the Federal Leaking Underground Storage 
Tank (LUST) Trust Fund (approximately $1.2 million per year) to clean up contaminated sites where a solvent O/O cannot be 
identified. </p>
<h3><b>USTMP - GUST Trust Fund Administration</b> </h3>
<p>Every UST O/O is required to have insurance or other financial assurance to ensure that leaks can be properly cleaned up. 
Georgia provides O/O with such a mechanism through the Georgia Underground Storage Tank (GUST) Trust Fund. The 
GUST Trust Fund is financed by a voluntary Environmental Assurance Fee (EAF) paid on each gallon of petroleum product 
delivered to regulated tanks in Georgia. The EAF can be adjusted by the Board of Natural Resources up to one cent per 
gallon. As of June 1996, the EAF was 0.2 cents per gallon and provides approximately $10 million/year to the GUST Trust 
Fund. Approximately 95% of the regulated community participate in the GUST Trust Fund. The fund provides each 
participating O/O with $1 million in corrective action and third-party liability coverage. Non-participating O/O must carry 
private insurance. </p>
<p>Coverage includes cleaning up leaked petroleum product, correcting environmental damage, supplying drinking water, and 
compensating third parties for personal injury or property damage. Interest from the Trust Fund helps pay for the cost of 
administering the Program. </p>
<p>To be eligible for reimbursement from the Trust Fund, the O/O must have paid the EAF and be in substantial compliance with 
UST rules and regulations. </p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
