<head>
<title>Geologic Survey Branch Narrative</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000">
<h1 align=center>GEOLOGIC SURVEY BRANCH</h1>
<p align=center>Dr. William H. McLemore, State Geologist<br>
19 Martin Luther King, Jr. Drive, Room 400<br>
Atlanta, Georgia 30334<br>
656-3214<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p>The Geologic Survey provides assistance to the Environmental Protection Division, other state and federal agencies, and the 
Georgia public in properly protecting, managing, regulating, and allocating Georgia's earth and water resources. The Survey 
conducts and encourages relevant environmental and earth and water resource investigations throughout the state; publishes 
pertinent results; assists the public in understanding and protecting Georgia's natural resources; and acts as a clearinghouse for 
such data. The Survey regulates exploration for petroleum and natural gas, regulates underground injection, and licenses water 
well contractors. The Survey assists the Director in coordinating a statewide groundwater policy of antidegradation. The 
Survey also provides accurate, up-to-date, multiscale topographic maps and digital data for Geographic Information Systems. 
The Survey issues certification for environmentally sensitive property (conservation use land).</p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h2>TECHNICAL INVESTIGATIONS PROGRAM</h2>
<p>Dr. Earl A. Shapiro<br>
404/656-3214<br>
</p>
<p>The Technical Investigations Program investigates those aspects of Georgia's geology that directly affect earth and water 
management decisions. The primary audiences of these investigations are EPD and state/local governmental agencies (including 
consultants who submit reports to governmental agencies).</p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h2>REGULATORY SUPPORT PROGRAM</h2>
<p>B. Roger Carter<br>
404/656-3214<br>
</p>
<p>The Regulatory Support Program either regulates specific environmental programs or provides relevant geologic and 
hydrologic data so that other Branches of EPD or other governmental agencies can better or more effectively regulate 
environmental programs. The primary audience of the Regulatory Support Program is EPD/EPA/State agencies and local 
governments.</p>
<hr>
</body>

</html>
