<html>

<head>
<title>Program Coordination Branch Narrative</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="images/seal160s.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000">
<h1 align=center>PROGRAM COORDINATION 
BRANCH</h1>
<p align=center>James L. Setser, Chief <br>
205 Butler Street, S.E., Suite 1152 <br>
Atlanta, Georgia 30334 <br>
656-4713 <br>
</p>
<hr>
<p>The Program Coordination Branch contains those functions which are Division-wide in 
scope. While many of the activities such as Laboratory Operations are supportive of the six 
other branches, discrete responsibility (compliance monitoring of 5,000 permitted facilities) 
is also carried out by the Branch. Enforcement, permitting, surveillance, and site review are 
included within the activities of the Program Coordination Branch's programs. </p>
<h2>EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM</h2>
<p>Bert Langley, Program Manager <br>
404/656-6905</p>
<p>The Emergency Response Program is tasked with the primary responsibility of responding 
to spills or releases of oil or hazardous materials on a 24 hour basis. Team members are on 
constant call to respond to the nearly 3,000 spills reported to EPD each year. A 24 hour 
Emergency Operations Center is manned by radio operators who receive the calls and relay 
the information to Emergency Response Team (ERT) members. The ERT also investigates 
high priority complaints which may not be emergencies, but need handling quicker than the 
various programs could respond. The program consists of six Emergency Response 
Specialists, the Program Manager and a secretary. <br>
</p>
<h2><a href="rad_prog.html">ENVIRONMENTAL RADIATION PROGRAM</a></h2>
<p><a href="mailto:Jim_Hardeman@mail.dnr.state.ga.us">James C. Hardeman</a>, Program Manager <br>
404/362-2675</p>
<p>Operates a statewide environmental radiation monitoring network, concentration on areas 
near commercial or defense-related nuclear facilities. Provides radioanalytical support to 
EPD and staff and serves as the primary state responder to incidents involving radioactive 
materials pursuant to Annex 12 (Hazardous Materials) of the Natural Disaster Operations 
Plan (NDOP) and the Radiological Emergency Plan (REP). Issues permits for 
concentration, storage or disposal of low-level radioactive waste material, and oversees 
remedial actions involving radioactive materials.</p>
<h2>ENVIRONMENTAL TOXICOLOGY 
COORDINATOR</h2>
<p>Randall O. Manning, Ph.D., D.A.B.T. <br>
404/656-4713</p>
<p>The Environmental Toxicology Coordinator provides the Division with technical and 
scientific advice and assistance to all programs concerned with the toxicity of environmental 
contaminants, especially those which may prove a threat to human health or the 
environment. Additionally, the toxicologist provides the necessary professional and scientific 
expertise required to peer review risk assessments, health assessments, and other scientific 
publications that evaluate environmental health issues. <br>
</p>
<h2>INFORMATION MANAGEMENT</h2>
<p>Ted Jackson <br>
404/656-6593</p>
<p>Manages and maintains Division-wide and Department-wide computational resources to 
assist EPD and DNR programs in meeting their commitments. Assists DNR associates in 
planning, developing and maintaining database applications residing on the Division or 
Department computers. Maintains wide-area communication network linkages with U.S. 
Environmental Protection Agency and some DNR offices. Assists DNR associates in 
learning database applications, programming, and access to EPA national environmental 
databases. <br>
</p>
<h2>LABORATORY PROGRAM</h2>
<p>Kerry Wilkes, Acting Program Manager <br>
404/853-7916</p>
<p>The Laboratory Program provides chemical and bacteriological analysis to support the 
branches of the Division for analysis of Air, Water, and Solids. <br>
</p>
<h2><a href="rad_prog.html">RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS PROGRAM</a></h2>
<p><a href="mailto:Tom_Hill@mail.dnr.state.ga.us">Thomas E. Hill</a>, Program Manager <br>
404/362-2675</p>
<p>Georgia, an Agreement State with the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC), is 
responsible for regulating the use of radioactive materials, other than at nuclear reactors and 
on Federal facilities within the State. The Radioactive Materials Program has the 
responsibility for administering the provisions of the Radiation Control Act. This 
responsibility is carried out through a statewide program of licensing and inspection of the 
users of radioactive material. Facilities regulated by the Program include: hospitals, doctors 
offices, radiopharmacies, industrial radiography, colleges and universities, environmental 
laboratories (private and state), industrial plants using gauging devices, and consultants. <br>
</p>
<h2><a href="regions.html">REGION OFFICES</a></h2>
<p>Northwest Region Program Manager, Clark Reynolds, 404/362-2671 <br>
Northeast Region Program Manager, Bob Bishop, 706/369-6376 <br>
Middle Region Program Manager, Ed Jarrett, 912/751-6612 <br>
Southeast Region Program Manager, Larry Rogers, 912/264-7284 <br>
Southwest Region Program Manager, Tommy Tanner, 912/430-4144</p>
<p>Environmental specialists in five region offices perform compliance/enforcement inspections 
of assigned facilities which include drinking water, wastewater, air quality, solid waste, 
underground storage tank (UST), scrap tires and land disturbing activities. Specialists 
respond to citizen complaints, emergencies and special coordinated investigations with other 
EPD programs and local/state agencies. Regions are geographically divided into Northwest, 
Northeast, Middle, Southeast and Southwest offices. <br>
</p>
<h2>TRAINING</h2>
<p>Thomas B. Payne, Coordinator <br>
404/362-2673</p>
<p>Assess the training needs of the Division, inventories available resources, and procures 
training to meet those needs. Obtains training at the request of various work groups in the 
Division. Manages the Division Training facilities at the Tradeport Office complex. 
Maintains a directory of training available from outside vendors for the convenience of 
associates. Provides Total Quality Training for new associates on an ongoing basis.</p>
<hr>
