<html>

<head>
<title>Municipal Engineering Program</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1 align=center>Municipal Engineering Program</h1>
<p align=center><strong>Pete Maye</strong>, Program Manager<br>
205 Butler Street S.E., Suite 1058 East<br>
Atlanta, Georgia 30334<br>
Telephone: (404) 656-4769 | Fax: (404) 657-7379<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p>The Municipal Engineering Program (MEP) is a multidisciplinary group of environmental engineers and specialists, 
administrators, and data managers involved in a wide range of Water Protection Branch activities. The MEP stresses flexibility 
in its approach to meeting the goals of the Branch with units actively involved in engineering, technical assistance and 
education, nonpoint source controls, and data management. </p>
<hr>
<h3 align=center><a name="objectives">OBJECTIVES</a></h3>
<ol>
<li>To successfully complete the Federal Construction Grants Program closeout strategy by providing technical assistance 
to grantees and administering, in a professional and timely manner, all procedures as delegated by the USEPA.</li>
<li>To provide funding for the State's sewerage needs by continuing to administer the State Revolving Loan Program 
through the FY 1993 Capitalization Grant funds, as authorized by the Federal Clean Water Act of 1987, and by 
providing technical assistance to the loan programs of the Georgia Environmental Facilities Authority.</li>
<li>To ensure that the State's wastewater collection and treatment systems are planned, designed, and constructed in 
accordance with acceptable engineering practices and permit requirements.</li>
<li>To ensure wastewater treatment plant permit compliance and infrastructure protection by providing technical and 
financial guidance and training to community officials and facility operators. </li>
<li>To minimize nonpoint source pollution due to land disturbing activities.</li>
<li>To manage data and project tracking efficiently and effectively via computer databases.</li>
</ol>
<hr>
