<html>

<head>
<title>Municipal Permitting Program</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1 align=center>Municipal Permitting Program</h1>
<p align=center><strong>Jeff Larson</strong>, Program Manager<br>
4244 International Pkwy, Suite 110 <br>
Atlanta, GA 30354<br>
Telephone: (404) 362-2680 Fax: (404) 362-2691<br>
</p>
<hr>
<h3 align=center><a name="goal">GOAL</a></h3>
<p>To process and issue enforceable NPDES, LAS, and Industrial Pretreatment permits to each municipal and indirect industrial 
wastewater discharger, to determine on a continuing basis whether or not the permittee is in compliance with its permit, and to 
insure on a continuous basis that violations of State water quality laws, permit limitations, and compliance schedules by 
permittees are responded to by the State and resolved between the State and the discharger in a timely and appropriate 
manner. </p>
<hr>
<h3 align=center><a name="objectives">OBJECTIVES</a></h3>
<ol>
<li>To insure consistent, enforceable, high quality permits are issued for new and existing facilities that will protect the 
State's water quality. The permits will be based on the following: wasteload allocation models, stream use designations, 
facility designs, and State and Federal regulations on &quot;best available technologies&quot; and any toxics data. <ol Type="a">
<li>Draft permits in accordance with established procedures. Permits will be ready for the Director's signature 30 
days prior to expiration to insure there is no backlog of expired permits. </li>
<li>Take all actions necessary for the issuance or denial of permits within 90 days of receipt of completed 
applications. Time needed to obtain additional information from the permittee or to conduct a public hearing will 
be excluded from the 90 day period. </li>
<li>The effluent limits will be consistent with the State Rules and Regulations for addressing toxic pollutants for which 
State Water Quality Regulations have been established and in accordance with the State's Reasonable Potential 
Procedures. </li>
<li>Track municipal storm water reporting requirements and permit compliance. </li>
<li>Continue with a process to attain from EPA delegation to regulate sludge and require sludge handlers to meet all 
Federal and State regulations (if the necessary resources are available).</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>To determine on a continuing basis the compliance status of permits issued through discharge monitoring review, facility 
compliance and sampling inspections and complaint investigations. <ol Type="a">
<li>To conduct an inspection on major facilities with significant problems in accordance with the Enforcement 
Management Strategy. </li>
<li>To conduct and document an inspection on all assigned minor municipal (at a minimum, once every three years) 
and an annual inspection and sampling visit on industrial pretreatment facilities with State issued permits. </li>
<li>To conduct an Industrial Pretreatment Compliance inspection or an Audit annually on all approved programs in 
accordance with the Industrial Pretreatment Compliance Strategy. </li>
<li>To continue tracking local pretreatment program revisions through pretreatment compliance inspections, audits, 
and the enforcement management system. These revisions are necessary to comply with the General Pretreatment 
Regulations, as amended. </li>
<li>To review discharge monitoring reports monthly to insure reports are filed, compliance is achieved and the data is 
entered into PCS. </li>
<li>To provide quality review and approval of documents, such as industrial pretreatment programs, industrial 
pretreatment annual reports, and storm water program annual reports in accordance with the current procedures. </li>
<li>To perform Adequacy of Treatment review for new development and make recommendations as to certification 
based on the impact on the water pollution control plant. </li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>To initiate timely and effective enforcement action to control discharges that fail to meet permit limits or violate State or 
Federal Water Quality Laws. <ol Type="a">
<li>To initiate appropriate and uniform enforcement action when noncompliance is documented in accordance with 
the Enforcement Management Strategy (to include limits violations and missed report submittal deadlines). The 
Enforcement Management Strategy rating report will be updated on a quarterly basis. </li>
<li>To exhaust all nonenforcement remedies available, technical assistance and notification of the facility of corrective 
action needed, prior to initiation of formal enforcement action. This condition does not allow for any waivers from 
the time frames specified in the Enforcement Management Strategy. However, when the violation is considered 
intentional, flagrant or poses a health problem, immediate action will be taken. </li>
<li>To execute Consent Orders with facilities that violate Permit or Water Quality laws, such that the Orders will 
bring about the expeditious resolution of the noncompliance and establish a procedure that will prevent or control 
a recurrence of the violation. </li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>To utilize as a management tool the automated data processing systems available to the fullest extent possible. <ol Type="a">
<li>To establish a system to insure data is handled once and that maintaining the data management system does not 
burden the staff. The data management system must support the staff of the program and must facilitate the 
management of the program resources. </li>
<li>To track the following on a monthly basis: <ul>
<li>-Permit applications being processed </li>
<li>-Permits expiring within 240 days </li>
<li>-Inspections conducted </li>
<li>-Facilities under sewer ban </li>
<li>-Facilities under enforcement order </li>
<li>-Significant noncompliance <ol Type="a">
<li>Limits </li>
<li>Schedules</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>-Enforcement orders issued </li>
<li>-Reportable Noncompliance (RNC) and Significant Noncompliance (SNC) for approved local 
pretreatment programs </li>
<li>-PPETS (Pretreatment Permits and Enforcement Tracking systems)/WENBE (Water Enforcement 
National Data Base) </li>
<li>-Pretreatment Annual Report Submittals </li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li>To provide training for staff on an as needed basis as well as scheduled training for new personnel in accordance with 
the program's training procedures in the following areas: <ol>
<li>General Overview </li>
<li>NPDES Permits </li>
<li>LAS Permits	</li>
<li>Inspections	</li>
<li>Pretreatment	</li>
<li>Complaints	</li>
<li>Enforcement Management	</li>
<li>Sludge	</li>
<li>Writing Workshops (outside MPP) </li>
<li>Storm water </li>
<li>CSO Overview </li>
<li>Toxics Control </li>
<li>Information Management Systems/Computers </li>
<li>Wastewater Training Courses (outside MPP) </li>
<li>Seminars (outside MPP) </li>
</ol>
<p>The training program will include an ongoing study program on wastewater treatment so that new associates are 
properly trained for inspection activities. </p>
</li>
</ol>
<hr>
<p align=center>[<a href="index.htm">Back to Water Protection Branch</a>]<br>
[<a href="wqmp.htm">Water Quality Management Program</a>] [<a href="wmep.htm">Municipal Engineering Program</a>] [<a href="wiwp.htm">Industrial Wastewater Program</a>]<br>
</p>
<hr>
</body>

