<h1 align="center">Radiation Control in Georgia</h1>

<table border="2" cellpadding="2" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" colspan="2"><h3 align="center">Georgia
        Department of Natural Resources -- Environmental Protection
        Division </h3>
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="30%"><a href="env_rad.html"><strong>Environmental Radiation
        Program</strong></a></td>
        <td width="30%"><strong>Operates a statewide
        environmental radiation monitoring network, concentrating
        on areas near commercial or defense-related nuclear
        facilities. Maintains a 24-hour capability to respond to
        radiological emergencies anywhere in the State of
        Georgia. Provides radiation training to state and/or
        local response personnel. Provides by contract for the
        operation of the </strong><a href="erl.html"><strong>Environmental
        Radiation Laboratory</strong></a><strong> (ERL) at </strong><a
        href="http://www.gatech.edu/"><strong>Georgia Tech</strong></a><strong>,
        which performs radiochemical analyses for the Program,
        and provides radioanalytical support to other EPD programs,
        including the </strong><a
        href="http://167.193.53.2/EPD/wrb/index.htm"><strong>Drinking
        Water Program</strong></a><strong> and the </strong><a
        href="http://167.193.53.2/EPD/gsb/gsnar.htm"><strong>Georgia
        Geologic Survey</strong></a><strong>. Provides oversight
        for remedial actions involving radioactive materials.
        Operates a permitting program for the concentration,
        storage and disposal of low-level radioactive waste
        material. Follow this link to our </strong><a
        href="info.htm"><strong>rules</strong></a><strong>.</strong></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="30%"><a href="rad_mat.html"><strong>Radioactive Materials
        Program</strong></a></td>
        <td width="30%"><strong>Georgia, an Agreement State with
        the </strong><a href="http://www.nrc.gov/"><strong>U.S.
        Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC)</strong></a><strong>,
        is responsible for regulating the use of radioactive
        materials, other than at nuclear reactors and on Federal
        facilities within the State. The Radioactive Materials
        Program has the responsibility for administering the
        provisions of the Georgia Radiation Control Act (O.C.G.A.
        31-13). This responsibility is carried out through a
        statewide program of licensing and inspection of the
        users of radioactive material. Facilities regulated by
        the Program include: hospitals, doctors offices,
        radiopharmacies, industrial radiography, colleges and
        universities, environmental laboratories (private and
        state), industrial plants using gauging devices, and
        consultants. Follow this link to our </strong><a
        href="info.htm"><strong>rules</strong></a><strong>.</strong></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" colspan="2"><h3 align="center">Other
        State Agencies </h3>
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="30%"><strong>X-Ray</strong></td>
        <td valign="top" width="30%"><strong>The Diagnostic
        Services Unit in the Department of Human Resources (DHR)
        regulates the uses of machine-produced radiation,
        including X-ray machines. Contact the DHR Diagnostic
        Services Unit at (404) 657-5400 for more information.</strong></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="30%"><a
        href="http://www.state.ga.us/PSC/scope.htm#trans"><strong>Transportation Permits</strong></a></td>
        <td width="30%"><strong>The Georgia Public Service
        Commission (PSC) regulates the transportation of
        hazardous materials, including radioactive materials. PSC
        requires either a single-trip or an annual transportation
        permit for transportation of radioactive material in or
        through the State of Georgia. Contact the PSC SafetyNet
        Division at (404) 559-6611 for more information.</strong></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="30%"><a
        href="http://www.state.ga.us/GEMA/"><strong>Emergency Planning</strong></a><strong> </strong></td>
        <td valign="top"><strong>The Georgia Emergency Management
        Agency (GEMA) is responsible for overall planning and
        coordination of the state's response to disasters, both
        natural and man-made. GEMA is responsible for maintaining
        the state Radiological Emergency Plan (REP). Contact the GEMA
        Chief of Radiological Programs at (404) 635-7230 for more
        information.</strong></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td colspan="2"><p align="center"><a
        href="http://www.sph.umich.edu/group/eih/UMSCHPS/states.htm"><font
        size="4"><strong>Radiation Protection Programs in Other
        States</strong></font></a><strong> </strong></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>

