<html>

<head>
<title>Georgia Environmental Radiation Program</title>
<meta name="resource-type" content="document">
<meta name="description" content="Georgia Environmental Radiation Program">
<meta name="distribution" content="global">
<meta name="copyright" content="1996 Georgia Department of Natural Resources">
<meta name="Author" content="Jim Hardeman">
<meta name="keywords" content="environmental radiation radioactive nuclear monitoring emergency response preparedness">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="images/seal160s.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#0000EE" vlink="#FF00FF" alink="#FF0000">
<h2 align=center>Georgia Department of Natural Resources</h2>
<h2 align=center>Environmental Protection Division</h2>
<h2 align=center>Environmental Radiation&#160;Program</h2>
<hr>
<p><font size=4><strong>Recognizing that the operation of nuclear facilities may affect environmental radiation levels 
by introducing man-made radioactive materials into the environment, in 1976 the </strong></font><a href="http://www.state.ga.us/"><font size=4><strong>Georgia 
General Assembly</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> amended the Georgia Radiation Control Act (O.C.G.A. 31-13) to provide 
the Environmental Protection Division (</strong></font><a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/epd/"><font size=4><strong>EPD</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>) of the Georgia Department of Natural 
Resources (</strong></font><a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/"><font size=4><strong>DNR</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>) with responsibility for monitoring of radiation and radioactive materials in 
the environment. Since that time, EPD has operated extensive </strong></font><a href="tld_map.html"><font size=4><strong>radiation monitoring networks</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> 
at nine (9) facilities in or bordering Georgia to determine if radioactive materials are being 
released into the environment in quantities sufficient to adversely affect the health and safety 
of the citizens of Georgia or the quality of Georgia's environment. These facilities are: </strong></font></p>
<p><font size=3><strong>(1) </strong></font><a href="http://www.southernco.com/www/gpc/gpchpage.htm"><font size=3><strong>Georgia Power Company</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong> </strong></font><a href="hatch.html"><font size=3><strong>Edwin I. Hatch Nuclear Plant</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>, located in Appling County, Georgia; <br>
(2) </strong></font><a href="http://www.alapower.com/"><font size=3><strong>Alabama Power Company</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong> </strong></font><a href="farley.html"><font size=3><strong>Joseph M. Farley Nuclear Plant</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>, located in Houston County, Alabama; <br>
(3) </strong></font><a href="http://www.southernco.com/www/gpc/gpchpage.htm"><font size=3><strong>Georgia Power Company</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong> </strong></font><a href="vogtle.html"><font size=3><strong>Vogtle Electric Generating Plant</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>, located in Burke County, Georgia; <br>
(4) </strong></font><a href="http://www.doe.gov/"><font size=3><strong>U.S. Department of Energy</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong> </strong></font><a href="srs.html"><font size=3><strong>Savannah River Site</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>, located in Aiken and Barnwell Counties, South Carolina; <br>
(5) </strong></font><a href="http://www.gnatnet.net/~kingsbay/baseindx.htm"><font size=3><strong>U.S. Navy</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>, </strong></font><a href="kingsbay.html"><font size=3><strong>Naval Submarine Base, Kings Bay</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>, located in Camden County, Georgia; <br>
(6) </strong></font><a href="neely.html"><font size=3><strong>Georgia Tech Research Reactor</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>, located in Fulton County, Georgia; <br>
(7) </strong></font><a href="dawson.html"><font size=3><strong>Dawson Forest Wildlife Management Area</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>, located in Dawson County, Georgia; <br>
(8) Tennessee Valley Authority </strong></font><a href="sequoyah.html"><font size=3><strong>Sequoyah Nuclear Plant</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>, located in Hamilton County, Tennessee; <br>
(9) </strong></font><a href="http://www.dukepower.com/"><font size=3><strong>Duke Power Company</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong> </strong></font><a href="oconee.html"><font size=3><strong>Oconee Nuclear Plant</strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>, located in Oconee County, South Carolina. </strong></font></p>
<p><font size=4><strong>Program associates perform </strong></font><a href="tld.html"><font size=4><strong>direct radiation measurements</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> and collect samples of 
environmental media such as </strong></font><a href="airsamp.html"><font size=4><strong>air</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>, </strong></font><a href="fish.html"><font size=4><strong>fish</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>, </strong></font><a href="gwat.html"><font size=4><strong>ground water</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>, </strong></font><a href="rain.html"><font size=4><strong>rain</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>, </strong></font><a href="sediment.html"><font size=4><strong>stream sediment</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>, </strong></font><a href="swat.html"><font size=4><strong>surface water</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>, 
</strong></font><a href="soilveg.html"><font size=4><strong>soil, and vegetation</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> near these facilities and at background locations around the state. 
Environmental samples are analyzed for radioactive materials at the </strong></font><a href="erl.html"><font size=4><strong>Environmental 
Radiation Laboratory</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> (ERL) at </strong></font><a href="http://www.gatech.edu/"><font size=4><strong>Georgia Tech</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>, which is operated under contract to EPD.</strong></font></p>
<p><font size=4><strong>By Executive Order of the Governor, the Department of Natural Resources is the lead state 
agency for response to and technical assessment of peacetime radiological emergencies. This 
responsibility is implemented by the Environmental Radiation Program, with assistance from 
the </strong></font><a href="rad_mat.html"><font size=4><strong>Radioactive Materials Program</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>. The Program also plays a major role in </strong></font><a href="REP.html"><font size=4><strong>radiological 
emergency planning</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> and preparedness efforts for the state, including participation in 
radiological emergency exercises at Plant Hatch, Plant Vogtle, Plant Farley, and the 
Savannah River Site. Program associates are also involved in emergency preparedness 
activities related to the transportation of radioactive materials, including </strong></font><a href="http://www.rw.doe.gov/"><font size=4><strong>spent nuclear fuel</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> 
and </strong></font><a href="http://www.wipp.carlsbad.nm.us/"><font size=4><strong>transuranic waste</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>, through the State of Georgia.</strong></font></p>
<p><font size=4><strong>The Environmental Radiation Program regulates the disposal of radioactive waste in 
Georgia through the </strong></font><a href="info.htm"><font size=4><strong>Rules and Regulations for Radioactive Waste Material Disposal</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>. 
Georgia is a member of the Southeast Interstate Low-Level Radioactive Waste Management 
Compact (Southeast Compact), along with the states of Alabama, Florida, Mississippi, North 
Carolina, Tennessee and Virginia. Much of the low-level radioactive waste generated in the 
region is currently disposed of at the Barnwell facility in South Carolina. The Southeast 
Compact is currently working towards development of the next regional disposal facility in 
North Carolina. </strong></font></p>
<p><font size=4><strong>You may </strong></font><a href="address.html"><font size=4><strong>contact</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> program associates, and you may also look at our </strong></font><a href="links.html"><font size=4><strong>links</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>. There will be </strong></font><a href="coming_soon.html"><font size=4><strong>more</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> 
to see and do in the coming months.</strong></font></p>
<p><font size=4><strong>Please take the time to sign our </strong></font><a href="guest.htm"><font size=4><strong>Guest Book</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>. Your </strong></font><a href="mailto:Jim_Hardeman@mail.dnr.state.ga.us"><font size=4><strong>feedback</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> on this site is greatly 
appreciated.</strong></font></p>
