<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Edwin I. Hatch Nuclear Plant</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Edwin I. Hatch Nuclear Plant</H2>

<P>&nbsp;<IMG SRC="hatch.jpg" HSPACE=5 HEIGHT=225 WIDTH=299 ALIGN=RIGHT></P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.southernco.com/www/gpc/gpchpage.htm">Georgia Power
Company</A> operates the <A HREF="http://www.nrc.gov/AEOD/pib/reactors/321/321toc.html">Edwin
I. Hatch Nuclear&nbsp;Plant</A>, located along the banks of the Altamaha
River in Appling County, Georgia approximately 10 miles north of the city
of Baxley. Plant Hatch consists of two (2)&nbsp;General Electric Boiling
Water Reactors (BWR's). Unit 1 is rated at 786 megawatts electric (MWe),
and was placed into service in December 1974. Unit 2 is rated at 795 MWe,
and was placed into service in September 1979.</P>

<P>EPD has forty-nine (49) thermoluminescent dosimeters (<A HREF="tld.html">TLDs</A>)&nbsp;deployed
around Plant Hatch monitor ambient gamma radiation levels. EPD also operates
three (3)&nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="airsamp.html">air and rainwater samplers</A>
around Plant Hatch. During quarterly monitoring visits, EPD associates
collect <A HREF="soilveg.html">soil, vegetation, groundwater</A> and <A HREF="swat.html">surface
water</A> in Appling, Jeff Davis, Tattnall and Toombs counties. Georgia
Power company provides samples of <A HREF="milk.html">milk</A> collected
at local dairies, and and EPD associates annually collect samples of <A HREF="sediment.html">sediment
</A>and <A HREF="fish.html">fish</A> from the Altamaha River. All samples
are analyzed for the presence of radioactive materials at the Environmental
Radiation Laboratory (<A HREF="erl.html">ERL</A>), located on the campus
at Georgia Tech. Standard analyses include gross <A HREF="alpha.html">alpha</A>,
gross <A HREF="beta.html">beta</A>, <A HREF="tritium.html">H-3 (tritium)</A>,
<A HREF="gamma.html">gamma </A>spectroscopy, <A HREF="strontium.html">strontium</A>-90
(Sr-90) and low-level <A HREF="iodine.html">iodine</A>-131 (I-131).</P>

<P>Click <A HREF="hnp_map.html">here</A> for a map of monitoring locations.</P>

<P>In 1986, some 141,000 gallons of water was spilled from the Plant Hatch
spent fuel pool to the environment. The estimated activity in the pool
water released was 373 millicuries (mCi) of fission and activation products
(i.e. cesium-137 (Cs-137), Cs-134, zinc-65 (Zn-65), cobalt-60 (Co-60) and
manganese-54 (Mn-54), and approximately 200 mCi of tritium. Much of this
activity was retained in a dry creekbed leading to an onsite cypress pond,
and Georgia Power performed prompt remedial action to remove the majority
of the activity. EPD monitoring after the incident, however, showed trace
concentrations of fission and activation products in river sediment downstream
of a pond overflow. Current environmental monitoring results, however,
show no evidence of releases of radioactive materials from Plant Hatch
to the environment.</P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

