<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Mobile Radiation Laboratory</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Mobile Radiation Laboratory</H2>

<P>The Environmental Radiation Program operates a Mobile Radiation&nbsp;Laboratory
(MRL). The primary purpose for the MRL&nbsp;is to provide rapid radiological
laboratory support to major radiological incidents. The MRL may also be
used to support remedial actions involving radioactive materials, such
as the Radiation Sterilizers, Inc.&nbsp;(RSI) cleanup.</P>

<P>The MRL is housed in a forty-foot (40') fifth wheel trailer, which is
towed by a Ford F-350 extended cab dual rear wheel pickup truck. Power
is provided either by a 50-amp 220-volt AC shore line hookup, or from an
Onan 12.5 kW propane-fueled generator. The MRL&nbsp;carries 80 gallons
of propane, enough fuel for 36 - 48 hours under full load. Heating and
air conditioning are provided by a 24,000 BTU residential heat pump. The
MRL&nbsp;has a sink in the sample preparation area, and a lavatory and
chemical toilet in the restroom, and has a forty (40)&nbsp;gallon capacity
for both water and waste.</P>

<P>Analytical systems aboard the MRL&nbsp;include a <A HREF="http://www.canberra.com">Canberra</A>
GENIE-AXP <A HREF="gamma.html">gamma</A> spectroscopy system running on
a 133-MHz Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC)&nbsp;Alpha AXP and a Packard
TR2500/AB automatic <A HREF="ls.html">liquid scintillation counter</A>.
The GENIE system is connected to two (2)&nbsp;high-purity intrinsic germanium
(HpGe) detectors -- one 25% efficient, the other 40% efficient -- both
configured for portable use. The GENIE system aboard the MRL&nbsp;is compatible
with the GENIE&nbsp;system at the <A HREF="erl.html">Environmental Radiation
Laboratory (ERL)</A>, and through the Internet or over modem, either system
may control detectors on the other.</P>

<P>The rear of the MRL&nbsp;provides office space, and a sofa in the office
folds out into a full-size bed to allow for 24-hour staffing, if required.</P>

<P>The MRL is wired for a 10-baseT computer network, and can accept up
to five (5)&nbsp;telephone lines. A &quot;pass-through&quot;&nbsp;cable
port allows the GENIE gamma spectroscopy system to be connected to a germanium
detector outside the MRL, if required.</P>

<P>Click <A HREF="mrl_plan.html">here</A> for the floor plan used in construction
of the MRL.</P>

<H2>
