<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Vogtle Electric Generating Plant</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Vogtle Electric Generating Plant</H2>

<P>&nbsp;<IMG SRC="vogtle.jpg" HSPACE=5 HEIGHT=225 WIDTH=300 ALIGN=RIGHT></P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.southernco.com/www/gpc/gpchpage.htm">Georgia Power
Company</A> operates the <A HREF="http://www.nrc.gov/AEOD/pib/reactors/424/424toc.html">Vogtle
Electric Generating Plant</A>, located on the banks of the Savannah River
in Burke County, Georgia approximately 17 miles east northeast of the city
of Waynesboro. Plant Vogtle consists of two (2)&nbsp;Westinghouse Pressurized
Water Reactors (PWR's), each rated at 1223 megawatts electric (MWe)&nbsp;gross
output. Georgia Power placed Unit 1 into commercial operation in June,
1987; Unit 2 in May, 1989.</P>

<P>Plant Vogtle is directly across the Savannah River from the <A HREF="http://www.srs.gov">Savannah
River Site</A>, and EPD uses a common network to monitor around the two
facilities. EPD has forty-nine (49) thermoluminescent dosimeters (<A HREF="tld.html">TLDs</A>)&nbsp;deployed
around Plant Vogtle and SRS to monitor ambient gamma radiation levels.
EPD also operates eleven (11)&nbsp;<A HREF="airsamp.html">air and rainwater
samplers</A> and seven (7)&nbsp;continuous <A HREF="water.html">water</A>
samplers around Plant Vogtle and SRS. During quarterly monitoring visits,
EPD associates collect <A HREF="soilveg.html">soil, vegetation</A> and
<A HREF="gwat.html">groundwater</A> in Burke, Richmond and Screven counties.
The Georgia Department of Agriculture provides samples of <A HREF="milk.html">milk</A>
collected from nearby dairies, and EPD associates annually collect samples
of <A HREF="sediment.html">sediment </A>and <A HREF="fish.html">fish</A>
from the Savannah River. EPD also collects samples of <A HREF="crops.html">crops</A>
such as corn, peaches, peanuts and pecans for radiochemical analysis. All
samples are analyzed for the presence of radioactive materials at the Environmental
Radiation Laboratory (<A HREF="erl.html">ERL</A>), located on the campus
at Georgia Tech. Standard analyses include gross <A HREF="alpha.html">alpha</A>,
gross <A HREF="beta.html">beta</A>, <A HREF="tritium.html">H-3 (tritium)</A>,
<A HREF="gamma.html">gamma </A>spectroscopy, <A HREF="strontium.html">strontium</A>-90
(Sr-90), low-level <A HREF="iodine.html">iodine</A>-131 (I-131) and <A HREF="pu.html">plutonium</A>-239
(Pu-239).</P>

<P>EPD&nbsp;monitoring, and results of monitoring conducted by other parties,
such as the <A HREF="http://www.state.sc.us/dhec/">South Carolina Department
of Health and Environmental Control (DHEC)</A>, SRS and Georgia Power,
indicate that activation products such as manganese-54 (Mn-54), cobalt-58
(Co-58) and Co-60 are present in trace concentrations in sediment and aquatic
vegetation immediately downstream of the Vogtle discharge. EPD has also
detected cesium-134 (Cs-134)&nbsp;in a limited number of fish downstream
from Vogtle. There are no other discernable radiological impacts which
can be attributed to the operation of Plant Vogtle.</P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

