<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Crop Sampling</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Crop Sampling</H2>

<P>In 1994, the Environmental Radiation&nbsp;Program began a program of
crop sampling and analysis within a 50-mile radius of the <A HREF="srs.html">Savannah
River Site (SRS)</A>. With the help of the Georgia Department of Agriculture
and County Extension agents, Program associates identified four crops --
corn, peaches, peanuts and pecans -- as being generally available in the
area, and as being likely to be available from the same locations year
after year. Again with the help of the Georgia Department of Agriculture
and County Extension agents, Program associates identified farmers and
growers (4 - 5 per crop) who were willing to participate in the crop sampling
and analysis program. Some growers donate crops, and others sell their
crops to the Program. </P>

<P>Upon receipt at the <A HREF="erl.html">Environmental Radiation Laboratory
(ERL)</A>, crop samples are shelled or shucked, as appropriate, and homogenized
into a single sample per location for analysis. Typically, gross <A HREF="alpha.html">alpha</A>,
gross <A HREF="beta.html">beta</A>, <A HREF="tritium.html">tritium</A>,
<A HREF="gamma.html">gamma</A> spectroscopy, <A HREF="strontium.html">strontium</A>-90
(Sr-90) and <A HREF="pu.html">plutonium</A>-239 (Pu-239) analyses are performed
on crop samples.</P>

<H2>
<HR width="100%"></H2>

<CENTER><P>[ <A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/index.htm">Home</A> |
<A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/news.htm">What's New</A> | <A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/toc.htm">TOC</A>
| <A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/feedback.htm">Feedback</A> | <A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/search.htm">Search</A>
]
<HR width="100%"></P></CENTER>

