<head>
<title>Savannah River Site</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Jim Hardeman">
<meta name="GENERATOR"
content="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</head>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE"
vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" background="whttxtr1.jpg">
<h2 align="CENTER">Savannah River Site</h2>
<p><img src="srcanyon.jpg" hspace="10" height="201" width="300"
align="LEFT">Westinghouse Savannah&#160;River Company (WSRC)
operates the <a href="http://www.doe.gov">U.S. Department of
Energy (DOE)</a>&#160;<a href="http://www.srs.gov">Savannah River
Site (SRS)</a>, a 300 square-mile site located in Aiken,
Allendale and Barnwell counties in South Carolina. Former
missions at SRS included production of plutonium and tritium for
the nation's nuclear deterrent capability. Production facilities
included five (5)&#160;nuclear production reactors, two
(2)&#160;chemical reprocessing plants, a fuel and target
fabrication facility, underground tanks for storage of high-level
liquid radioactive waste, and a low-level radioactive waste
disposal facilities. </p>
<p><img src="rtf.jpg" hspace="10" height="233" width="300"
align="RIGHT">The current missions at SRS are primarily related
to environmental restoration and waste management. Two new
facilities, the Defense Waste Processing Facility (DWPF)&#160;and
the Consolidated Incineration Facility (CIF) are due to begin
operations in 1996. DWPF will solidify high-level liquid
radioactive waste in a glass waste form. The resulting solid
waste form will be stored onsite. The CIF will be used to dispose
of certain hazardous and radioactive waste streams. SRS also has
a current defense mission -- the testing and recycling of tritium
reservoirs used in nuclear weapons. SRS is also producing
plutonium-238 (Pu-238) for use by the <a
href="http://www.nasa.gov">National Aeronautics and Space
Administration (NASA)</a>, including the 1997 <a
href="http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/cassini/">Cassini</a> mission to
Saturn.</p>
<p>Savannah&#160;River Site is directly across the Savannah River
from <a href="vogtle.html">Plant Vogtle</a>, and EPD uses a
common network to monitor around the two facilities. EPD has
forty-nine (49) thermoluminescent dosimeters (<a href="tld.html">TLDs</a>)&#160;deployed
around Plant Vogtle and SRS to monitor ambient gamma radiation
levels. EPD also operates eleven (11)&#160;<a href="airsamp.html">air
and rainwater samplers</a> and seven (7)&#160;continuous <a
href="water.html">water</a> samplers around Plant Vogtle and SRS.
During quarterly monitoring visits, EPD associates collect <a
href="soilveg.html">soil, vegetation</a> and <a href="gwat.html">groundwater</a>
in Burke, Richmond and Screven counties. The Georgia Department
of Agriculture provides samples of <a href="milk.html">milk</a>
collected from nearby dairies, and EPD associates annually
collect samples of <a href="sediment.html">sediment </a>and <a
href="fish.html">fish</a> from the Savannah River. EPD also
collects samples of <a href="crops.html">crops</a> such as corn,
peaches, peanuts and pecans for radiochemical analysis. All
samples are analyzed for the presence of radioactive materials at
the Environmental Radiation Laboratory (<a href="erl.html">ERL</a>),
located on the campus at Georgia Tech. Standard analyses include
gross <a href="alpha.html">alpha</a>, gross <a href="beta.html">beta</a>, <a
href="tritium.html">H-3 (tritium)</a>, <a href="gamma.html">gamma </a>spectroscopy, <a
href="strontium.html">strontium</a>-90 (Sr-90), low-level <a
href="iodine.html">iodine</a>-131 (I-131) and <a href="pu.html">plutonium</a>-239
(Pu-239).</p>
<p>EPD&#160;monitoring, and results of monitoring conducted by
other parties, such as the <a href="http://www.state.sc.us/dhec/">South
Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control (DHEC)</a>,
SRS and Georgia Power, shows evidence of current and prior
releases of radioactive materials from SRS. Elevated levels of
tritium due to airborne and liquid releases are routinely
detected in fish, milk, precipitation, surface water and
rainwater. Tritium has also been detected in shallow groundwater
in Burke County, Georgia, and the Georgia Geologic Survey is
attempting to determine the cause.</p>
<p>EPD monitoring also shows elevated concentrations of
cesium-137 (Cs-137) and strontium-90 (Sr-90)&#160;in fish
collected from the mouths of SRS site streams as they enter the
Savannah River. Cs-137, Sr-90 and cobalt-60 (Co-60)&#160;are also
found in stream sediments.</p>
<p> </p>
<hr width="100%">
<center>
<p>[ <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/index.htm">Home</a> | <a
href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/news.htm">What's New</a> | <a
