<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Naval Submarine Base, Kings Bay</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Naval Submarine Base, Kings Bay</H2>

<P>The <A HREF="http://www.navy.mil">U.S. Navy </A>operates the Naval Submarine
Base, Kings Bay in Camden County, Georgia, outside the city of St. Marys.
The Navy began operations at Kings Bay in 1979, when it began submarine
refit operations there for Poseidon-class submarines. The base now serves
as home port, refit site and training facility for Ohio-class submarines
in the Atlantic Fleet.</P>

<P>EPD&nbsp;has twenty-six (26) thermoluminescent dosimeters (<A HREF="tld.html">TLDs</A>)&nbsp;deployed
around Kings Bay to monitor ambient gamma radiation levels. On a periodic
basis, EPD associates also collect <A HREF="soilveg.html">soil, vegetation</A>
, <A HREF="swat.html">surface water</A>, <A HREF="sediment.html">sediment</A>
and <A HREF="gwat.html">groundwater</A>. All samples are analyzed for the
presence of radioactive materials at the Environmental Radiation Laboratory
(<A HREF="erl.html">ERL</A>), located on the campus at Georgia Tech. Standard
analyses include gross <A HREF="alpha.html">alpha</A>, gross <A HREF="beta.html">beta</A>,
<A HREF="tritium.html">H-3 (tritium)</A>, and <A HREF="gamma.html">gamma
</A>spectroscopy.</P>

<P>Click <A HREF="kbs_map.html">here</A> for a map of monitoring locations.</P>

<P>The results of EPD&nbsp;monitoring around Kings Bay show no evidence
of the release of radioactive materials. EPD has observed elevated gross
beta levels in seawater samples, due to naturally-occuring potassium-40
(K-40) in seawater.</P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

