<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Neely Nuclear Research Center</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Neely Nuclear Research Center</H2>

<P>&nbsp;The Neely Nuclear Research Center (NNRC) is located on the campus
of the <A HREF="http://www.gatech.edu">Georgia Institute of Technology</A>
in Atlanta. NNRC includes the Georgia Tech Research Reactor (GTRR), a 5-megawatt
thermal research reactor. The GTRR&nbsp;is used for training, research
and testing. In addition to the GTRR, the NNRC also contains facilities
for the preparation, storage and use of radioactive materials, including
a &quot;hot cell&quot; for handling large quantities of radioactive material.</P>

<P>EPD&nbsp;has fourteen (14) thermoluminescent dosimeters (<A HREF="tld.html">TLDs</A>)&nbsp;deployed
around the Neely Nuclear Research Center to monitor ambient gamma radiation
levels. During quarterly monitoring visits, EPD associates collect <A HREF="soilveg.html">soil
and vegetation</A> near NNRC. All samples are analyzed for the presence
of radioactive materials at the Environmental Radiation Laboratory (<A HREF="erl.html">ERL</A>),
located on the campus at Georgia Tech. Standard analyses include gross
<A HREF="alpha.html">alpha</A>, gross <A HREF="beta.html">beta</A>, <A HREF="tritium.html">H-3
(tritium)</A>, and <A HREF="gamma.html">gamma </A>spectroscopy.</P>

<P>Although Georgia Tech reports releases of measureable quantities of
argon-41 (Ar-41), a short-lived noble gas, EPD monitoring results do not
show any evidence of releases of radioactive materials from the NNRC. However,
direct radiation measurements at one (1)&nbsp;location, TLD 9, are consistently
elevated, due to the storage of radioactive materials in a &quot;barn&quot;
about 10 feet away. Although elevated, observed radiation levels at this
location are within state and federal regulatory limits, and are not due
to releases of radioactive materials from NNRC.</P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

