<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Dawson Forest Wildlife Management Area</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Dawson Forest Wildlife Management Area</H2>

<P>The City of Atlanta owns the 10,000 acre Dawson Forest Wildlife Management
Area in Dawson County,&nbsp;Georgia. The site was formerly owned by Lockheed
Aircraft Corporation, which operated the Georgia Nuclear Aircraft Laboratory
(GNAL)&nbsp;at the site from 1959 through the late 1960's under contract
to the U.S. Air Force. GNAL facilities, intended to provide design data
for use in the development of a nuclear propulsion system for aircraft,
included a 10-megawatt thermal MTR-type Pressurized Water Reactor (PWR),
a hot-cell and administrative and support facilities.</P>

<P>After termination of the nuclear aircraft program, the name of the facility
was changed to the Lockheed-Georgia Nuclear Laboratory, and the facilities
were used for a broad range of activities, including materials and biological
effects research and radioactive material source encapsulation. Lockheed
decommissioned the facility in 1971 and sold the property to the City of
Atlanta. Atlanta entered into a contract with the Georgia Forestry Commission
to manage the timber resources on the site, and Forestry entered into a
contract with the Department of Natural Resources (DNR) for management
of wildlife resources.</P>

<P>EPD began monitoring at Dawson Forest in 1976, shortly after amendments
to the Georgia Radiation&nbsp;Control Act gave EPD the responsibility for
environmental monitoring. Based on an aerial radiological survey of the
site, and ground explorations of &quot;hot spots&quot;, two (2)&nbsp;areas
of the site, the &quot;hot cell&quot; and the &quot;cooling off area&quot;&nbsp;were
restricted from public access, and remain restricted to this date. These
areas, totalling some four (4)&nbsp;acres, contained elevated concentrations
of cobalt-60 (Co-60) and exhibited elevated direct radiation levels in
excess of state and federal regulations for unrestricted access.</P>

<P>EPD&nbsp;has ten (10) thermoluminescent dosimeters (<A HREF="tld.html">TLDs</A>)&nbsp;deployed
on the Dawson Forest Wildlife Management Area to monitor ambient gamma
radiation levels. On a periodic basis, EPD associates also collect <A HREF="soilveg.html">soil,
vegetation</A> , <A HREF="swat.html">surface water</A>, <A HREF="sediment.html">sediment</A>
and <A HREF="gwat.html">groundwater</A>. All samples are analyzed for the
presence of radioactive materials at the Environmental Radiation Laboratory
(<A HREF="erl.html">ERL</A>), located on the campus at Georgia Tech. Standard
analyses include gross <A HREF="alpha.html">alpha</A>, gross <A HREF="beta.html">beta</A>,
<A HREF="tritium.html">H-3 (tritium)</A>, and <A HREF="gamma.html">gamma
</A>spectroscopy.</P>

<P>Results of EPD&nbsp;monitoring at Dawson Forest indicate that the Co-60
at Dawson Forest is in a relatively insoluble form, is not readily mobile,
and has remained in the areas previously identified and closed to public
access. Direct radiation measurements near a known &quot;hot spot&quot;
(TLD 8) remain slightly elevated, but are within regulatory limits for
direct radiation exposure. The reduction in radiation levels at TLD 8 over
time are consistent with the decay of Co-60. </P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

