<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Oconee Nuclear Plant</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Oconee Nuclear Plant</H2>

<P>&nbsp;<IMG SRC="oconee.jpg" HSPACE=5 HEIGHT=225 WIDTH=299 ALIGN=RIGHT></P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.dukepower.com/">Duke Power Company</A> operates
the Oconee Nuclear Plant, located approximately eight (8) miles northeast
of Seneca, South Carolina. The Oconee Nuclear Plant consists of three (3)&nbsp;Babcock
&amp;&nbsp;Wilcox Pressurized Water Reactors (PWR's). All three units are
rated at 866 megawatts electric (MWe). Unit 1 began commercial operation
in July 1973; Unit 2 in September 1974; Unit 3 in December 1974..</P>

<P>EPD&nbsp;has nine (9) thermoluminescent dosimeters (<A HREF="tld.html">TLDs</A>)&nbsp;deployed
around Oconee to monitor ambient gamma radiation levels. During quarterly
monitoring visits, EPD associates collect <A HREF="soilveg.html">soil,
vegetation</A> , <A HREF="swat.html">surface water</A> and <A HREF="gwat.html">groundwater</A>
in Franklin, Habersham, Hart, Stephens and Rabun counties. All samples
are analyzed for the presence of radioactive materials at the Environmental
Radiation Laboratory (<A HREF="erl.html">ERL</A>), located on the campus
at Georgia Tech. Standard analyses include gross <A HREF="alpha.html">alpha</A>,
gross <A HREF="beta.html">beta</A>, <A HREF="tritium.html">H-3 (tritium)</A>,
and <A HREF="gamma.html">gamma </A>spectroscopy.</P>

<P>Click <A HREF="onp_map.html">here</A> for a map of monitoring locations.</P>

<P>EPD&nbsp;environmental monitoring results show no evidence of the release
of radioactive materials to the environment from the Oconee Nuclear Plant.</P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

