<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Direct Radiation Measurements</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Direct Radiation Measurements</H2>

<P>The Environmental Radiation Program uses thermoluminescent dosimeters
(TLD's) to measure cumulative radiation <A HREF="exposure.html">exposure</A>
in the environment. A TLD consists of a number of crystalline chips of
calcium fluoride or lithium fluoride in a plastic carrier. When radiation
strikes the TLD, part of the energy of the radiation causes a deformation
in the crystalline matrix. The deformation remains &quot;frozen&quot; in
the crystal until it is heated above a certain temperature. When heated,
the deformation relaxes, and the crystal emits a pulse of light. By measuring
the amount of light given off, one can infer the amount of radiation energy
stored in the crystal, and thus the total exposure. A &quot;TLD&nbsp;Reader&quot;
heats the crystals, measures the amount of light given off, converts that
measurement to exposure (mR) and then &quot;anneals&quot; the crystals
to remove all deformations so that the TLD can be used again.</P>

<P>Environmental Radiation Program associates typically exchange TLD's
quarterly; TLD's at <A HREF="dawson.html">Dawson Forest</A> and <A HREF="kingsbay.html">Kings
Bay</A> are exchanged twice per year. TLD's are normally posted on telephone
poles or trees approximately 2 meters above the ground. Control badges
are used to measure, and correct for, the <A HREF="exposure.html">exposure</A>
recorded by the TLD's during transit both to and from the <A HREF="erl.html">Environmental
Radiation Laboratory (ERL)</A>.</P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P>[ <A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/index.htm">Home</A> |
