<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Exposure and Exposure Rate</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Exposure and Exposure Rate</H2>

<P>Thermoluminescent dosimeters (<A HREF="tld.html">TLD</A>'s) used by
the Environmental&nbsp;Radiation Program measure cumulative exposure over
a period of time. Exposure is defined as the amount of ionizing radiation
absorbed by a given quantity of air. The traditional unit for exposure
is the Roentgen, named for Wilhelm Roentgen, the discoverer of the X-ray.
One Roentgen (abbreviated R) is equivalent to the absorption of one (1)
erg of energy by one (1)&nbsp;gram of air. The metric unit for exposure
is the Gray (abbreviated Gy), and is equivalent to an energy absorption
of 100 ergs per gram of air.</P>

<P>For most penetrating radiation, particularly gamma radiation, there
is a direct correlation between exposure and dose. The traditional unit
of measurement of dose is the rem, and the metric unit is the Sievert (abbreviated
Sv). For gamma radiation, 1 R is approximately equal to 1 rem and 1 Gy
is approximately equal to 1 Sv. </P>

<P>All EPD direct radiation measurements are expressed as exposure rates,
or the exposure per unit time, usually as milliRoentgen (abbreviate mR)
or microRoengten (abbreviated uR). One mR equals one one-thousandth (0.001)
R; one uR equals one one-millionth (0.000001)&nbsp;R. TLD measurements
are normally expressed in milliRoentgen per year (mR/yr); instantaneous
measurements are recorded in microRoentgen per hour (uR/hr). Direct radiation
measurements performed during response to radiological incidents may be
expressed in either milliRoentgen per hour (mR/hr) or even Roentgen per
hour (R/hr), depending on the severity of the incident. By making the simplifying
assumptions above, measurements of exposure rate can be converted directly
to external dose rate.</P>

<H2>
<HR width="100%"></H2>

<CENTER><P>[ <A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/index.htm">Home</A> |
<A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/news.htm">What's New</A> | <A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/toc.htm">TOC</A>
| <A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/feedback.htm">Feedback</A> | <A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/search.htm">Search</A>
]</P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>
<HR width="100%"></P></CENTER>

