<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Air Sampling</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Air Sampling</H2>

<P>The&nbsp;Environmental Radiation Program operates sixteen (16)&nbsp;continuous
air samplers: eleven (11)&nbsp;around Plant <A HREF="vogtle.html">Vogtle</A>
and the <A HREF="srs.html">Savannah River Site</A>; three (3)&nbsp;around
Plant <A HREF="hatch.html">Hatch</A>, and two (2)&nbsp;around Plant <A HREF="farley.html">Farley</A>.
These samplers are designed to monitor for radioiodines and particulates.
A known volume of air is passed through sample collection media, which
after collection, undergo gross <A HREF="alpha.html">alpha</A>, gross <A HREF="beta.html">beta</A>
and <A HREF="gamma.html">gamma</A> spectroscopy analyses at the <A HREF="erl.html">Environmental
Radiation Laboratory (ERL)</A>. Samples from the SRS and Vogtle network
are also analyzed for <A HREF="strontium.html">strontium</A>-90 (Sr-90)&nbsp;and
<A HREF="pu.html">plutonium</A>-239 (Pu-239). Air sampling stations are
serviced twice per month under contractual arrangements with local emergency
management agencies.</P>

<P>Each air sampling site consists of a weatherproof housing, a vacuum
pump, a dry-gas flowmeter and a sampling head which holds a 47mm charcoal
cartridge and a 47mm glass-fiber particulate filter. Upon receipt at the
ERL, the charcoal cartridges are gamma counted immediately, to minimize
analysis errors due to the short <A HREF="halflife.html">half-life</A>
of radioiodines. The particulate filters are partitioned and composited
for quarterly gamma spectroscopy, Sr-90 and Pu-239 analyses.</P>

<P>The Environmental Radiation&nbsp;Program is currently testing a <A HREF="tritium.html">tritium</A>-in-air
sampling system and analysis procedures. The sampling system consists of
a low-flow dry gas flowmeter, and two (2)&nbsp;canisters of drierite. Tritium,
in the form of tritium oxide (i.e. a water molecule in which a tritium
atom has replaced a normal hydrogen atom) is adsorbed in the drierite medium.
At the laboratory, the drierite is heated, driving off the water vapor.
The water vapor is then analyzed for tritium content. </P>

<P>We expect to deploy tritium samplers at most, if not all, of the sampling
locations around the Savannah&nbsp;River Site and Plant Vogtle during 1996.</P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

