<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Activity</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Activity</H2>

<P>Quantities of radioactive materials are not measured in pounds or gallons,
like other materials. Radioactive materials are measured by their activity
-- the number of radioactive decays in a given amount of time.</P>

<P>The traditional unit of activity is the Curie (abbreviated Ci). One
Curie equals 37,000,000,000 decays per second. This quantity is the activity
present in one (1)&nbsp;gram of pure radium-226, and the unit is named
for Madame Marie Curie, the discoverer of radium. The metric unit for activity
is the Bequerel (abbreviated Bq) and it equals one (1)&nbsp;disintegration
per second.</P>

<P>Environmental radiation monitoring requires measurement of small quantities
of radioactive materials, and the results are best expressed as small multiples
of the Curie. Most EPD environmental radiation measurements are expressed
are expressed as <A HREF="concentration.html">concentrations</A> in units
of picoCurie (abbreviated pCi) per unit mass (typically a kilogram) or
volume (typically liters or cubic meters). A picoCurie is one one-trillionth
(0.000000000001 or 10<SUP>-12</SUP>) of a Curie. EPD air measurements are
expressed in femptoCuries (fCi) per cubic meter of air. A femptoCurie is
equal to one one-quadrillionth (0.000000000000001 or 10<SUP>-15</SUP>)
of a Curie.</P>

<P>Depending on the specific radioactive material and its <A HREF="halflife.html">half-life</A>,
as compared to the amount of time required to collect samples, transport
the samples to the laboratory and analyze them, the activity in a sample
at the time of analysis may be substantially less that the activity present
at the time of sample collection. This effect is especially important when
analyzing for materials which have a short half-life, such as iodine-131.
EPD analysis procedures account for radioactive decay during sample collection,
transport and analysis by &quot;decay correcting&quot; the activity back
to the middle of the sample collection period.</P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

