<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Fish Sampling</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Fish Sampling</H2>

<P>Once per year, Environmental Radiation Program associates, in conjunction
with personnel from the Wildlife Resources Division (WRD), collect samples
of fish from the Altamaha, Chattahoochee and Savannah Rivers upstream and
downstream of Plant <A HREF="hatch.html">Hatch</A>, Plant <A HREF="farley.html">Farley</A>
and <A HREF="srs.html">Savannah River Site (SRS)</A> and&nbsp;Plant <A HREF="vogtle.html">Vogtle</A>.
Collections typically consist of five (5)&nbsp;or more individuals of each
of three (3)&nbsp;species (typically bass, catfish and panfish) at each
sampling location. Fish are collected by electroshocking, pursuant to a
Scientific Collection Permit issued by WRD. Fish are frozen and shipped
on ice to the <A HREF="erl.html">Environmental Radiation Laboratory (ERL)</A>.</P>

<P>Once at the laboratory, panfish and bass are scaled and catfish are
skinned. Panfish are prepared into a single composite sample per location
by grinding whole fish. For catfish and bass, however, filets are prepared
into &quot;edible&quot; composites, and the remainder is prepared as a
&quot;non-edible&quot; composite. Both edible and non-edible fractions
are weighed, allowing their radionuclide concentrations to be mathematically
recombined into &quot;whole fish&quot; concentrations, if desired. Small
tissue samples are also set aside for <A HREF="tritium.html">tritium</A>
analysis.</P>

<P>Gross <A HREF="alpha.html">alpha</A> and gross <A HREF="beta.html">beta</A>
analyses are performed for screening purposes. All fish are also analyzed
by <A HREF="gamma.html">gamma</A> spectroscopy. Based on the results of
screening, select samples may also be analyzed for <A HREF="strontium.html">strontium</A>-90
(Sr-90) and <A HREF="pu.html">plutonium</A>-239 (Pu-239).</P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

