<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Radiological Emergency Planning</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Jim Hardeman">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000" BACKGROUND="whttxtr1.jpg">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>&nbsp;Radiological Emergency Planning</H2>

<P><A HREF="http://www.nrc.gov">Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC)</A>&nbsp;regulations
for commercial nuclear power plants require that the plant operator demonstrate
the adequacy of both onsite and offsite radiological emergency preparedness
efforts to protect public health and safety. NRC requires that plant operators
exercise their onsite emergency plan annually. </P>

<P>The <A HREF="http://www.fema.gov">Federal Emergency Management Agency
(FEMA)</A>&nbsp;requires that affected state and local governments exercise
their offsite radiological emergency plans every two (2)&nbsp;years. All
elements of the plan must be exercised every six (6) years, and several
&quot;core objectives&quot; such as protective action decision making,
radiological field monitoring and public warning must be demonstrated during
every exercise.</P>

<P>In general, detailed emergency plans are required for jurisdictions
within ten (10) miles of a commercial nuclear plant -- the 10-mile Emergency
Planning Zone (EPZ). In addition, jurisdictions within a 50-mile EPZ must
be prepared to deal with contaminated agricultural products. A state must
conduct an ingestion pathway exercise somewhere in the state once every
six (6)&nbsp;years. </P>

<P>Click here for a <A HREF="ga_map.html">map</A> of the 10 and 50 mile
EPZ's affecting Georgia. </P>

<P>The Georgia Emergency Management Agency (GEMA) and the Environmental
Protection Division (<A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/epd/">EPD</A>)&nbsp;of
the Georgia Department of Natural Resources (<A HREF="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us">DNR</A>)
cooperatively develop, maintain and implement the Georgia Radiological
Emergency Plan (REP). The REP&nbsp;plan consists of a Base Plan, and annexes
the commercial nuclear plants required by federal regulation (i.e. <A HREF="farley.html">Plant
Farley</A>, <A HREF="hatch.html">Plant Hatch</A> and <A HREF="vogtle.html">Plant
Vogtle</A>). In addition, the Georgia REP contains annexes for the U.S.
Department of Energy (DOE)&nbsp;<A HREF="srs.html">Savannah River Site
(SRS)</A>, the <A HREF="neely.html">Georgia Tech Research Reactor (GTRR)</A>
and the <A HREF="kingsbay.html">Naval Submarine Base, Kings Bay</A>, an
annex for facilities where Georgia is only affected by the 50-mile EPZ
(i.e. <A HREF="sequoyah.html">Sequoyah</A>, <A HREF="wattsbar.html">Watts
Bar</A> and <A HREF="oconee.html">Oconee</A>) and an annex dealing with
transportation accidents involving radioactive materials.</P>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

