<body background="images/seal160s.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#0000EE" vlink="#FF00FF" alink="#FF0000">
<p align=center><br>
</p>
<h3 align=center><strong>Georgia Department of Natural Resources</strong></h3>
<h3 align=center><strong>Environmental Protection Division</strong></h3>
<h3 align=center><strong>Radioactive Materials Program</strong></h3>
<hr>
<h3><strong>INTRODUCTION</strong></h3>
<p><strong>Public concern that radiation causes personal and environmental dangers create an increased demand for 
regulation of radioactive material and equipment using radioactive material. Technology for using radiation is 
changing quickly. Radioactive materials and nonionizing radiation such as lasers, affect medicine, industry and 
entertainment. Creative use of this changing technology challenges regulatory efforts to confirm proper and safe 
operation of complex new equipment.<br>
<br>
Although we may not think of it that way, we live in a radiation environment. Most of the radiation that we use 
daily is nonionizing radiation. We do not think of it as radiation. It is light to illuminate our homes and work place, 
it is microwaves to cook our food, it is radio and television signals to entertain and inform us, and it is tanning 
booths to give our bodies that year around summertime tan. Radioactive materials occur naturally in the ground 
we walk on, in the water we drink, the air we breathe, and in the foods we eat. Because we cannot see, hear, smell, 
taste, or feel the radiation from the radioactive materials that occur naturally we are not aware of these. Since we 
are not aware of these materials, we do not understand them and we perceive them as dangerous. <br>
<br>
Certain uses of radiation and radioactive material can be beneficial to you and me. We all know someone who has 
had a diagnostic nuclear medicine test, a x-ray, or a cancer treatment from a teletherapy machine. In these ways, 
radiation, radioactive material, and x-rays help doctors to diagnose diseases and problems or to treat diseases 
such as cancers.<br>
<br>
Radioactive material is beneficial to industry. Gauges containing radioactive material use the radiation from the 
material to measure the rate of flow, the density of materials and the thickness of materials in manufacturing 
processes.</strong></p>
<h3><strong>WHO WE ARE</strong></h3>
<p><strong>The history of the Radioactive Materials Program goes back to 1964. In 1964 the Radiation Control Act passed 
the Georgia Legislature. This act allowed the state to enter an agreement with the former United States Atomic 
Energy Commission. This agreement was signed on December 15, 1969. The state is now an agreement state with 
the </strong><a href="http://www.nrc.gov/"><strong>U. S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission</strong></a><strong>. Since July 1990, the Radioactive Materials Program has been in the 
Department of Natural Resources.</strong></p>
<h3><strong>WHAT WE DO</strong></h3>
<p><strong>The Radioactive Material Program administers the Department's radiation control program for radioactive 
materials. This program licenses the receipt, possession, use, storage, and disposal of radioactive materials. 
Before anyone can receive certain radioactive material he must apply for a license. This written application must 
include, at a minimum, the name of the applicant, his address, his training and experience in the safe handling and 
use of radioactive material. And list the radioactive isotopes he wishes to use and his procedures for the safe use 
and handling of the radioactive material.<br>
<br>
Program staff inspect the licensees on a schedule. This helps ensure that the user of radioactive material is using 
and disposing of the material in an environmentally safe manner that protects the public's health and safety. The 
inspection is a snapshot of the licensees' procedures for the safe use of their radioactive material. A very 
important aspect of the inspection is the accountability of the radioactive material received, used and disposed of. 
The licensee must use the radioactive material in compliance with the Radiation Control Act, the </strong><a href="info.htm"><strong>Rules and 
Regulations for Radioactive Material (Chapter 391-3-17)</strong></a><strong>, and the conditions of his license. <br>
<br>
Should a licensee have a problem with the use of radioactive material, the staff will respond to their emergency to 
help and advise with their recovery. The Environmental Radiation Program staff helps the Radioactive Materials 
staff in responding to these emergencies. Also, the Radioactive Materials Program staff helps the Environmental 
Radiation staff in responding to other emergencies that occur.</strong></p>
<h3><strong>PENALTIES</strong></h3>
<p><strong>Licensees who do not operate by the rules and their license may be subject to a civil penalty. The Radiation 
Control Act provides for the assessment of civil penalties up to $10,000.00 per day per violation. </strong></p>
<h3><strong>FUNDING</strong></h3>
<p><strong>A fee system supports the Radioactive Materials Program. Under this system the users of radioactive material 
support the regulatory activities of the Department. Applicants must pay an </strong><a href="info.htm"><strong>initial application fee, an annual fee, 
an amendment fee</strong></a><strong> for any requested changes to the license, and a </strong><a href="info.htm"><strong>fee for compliance inspections</strong></a><strong> done by staff of 
the Radioactive Materials Program.</strong></p>
<h3><strong>RULES AND REGULATIONS</strong></h3>
<p><a href="info.htm"><strong>Rules and regulations</strong></a><strong> adopted by the Department are compatible with the rules of the U. S. Regulatory 
Commission and other Agreement States. By being compatible the regulatory program provides for the safety of 
the citizens of Georgia and does not interfere with the free exercise of business across state lines. Under a policy 
called </strong><a href="reciproc.htm"><strong>reciprocity</strong></a><strong>, Georgia recognizes radioactive materials licenses issued by either the </strong><a href="http://www.nrc.gov/"><strong>U.S. Nuclear Regulatory 
Commission</strong></a><strong> or other Agreement States.</strong></p>
<hr>
<p align=center><font size=4><strong>Please take the time to sign our </strong></font><a href="guest.htm"><font size=4><strong>Guest Book</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>. You can also check out our </strong></font><a href="links.html"><font size=4><strong>Links</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>.</strong></font></p>
<p align=center><font size=4><strong>Your </strong></font><a href="mailto:Jim_Hardeman@mail.dnr.state.ga.us"><font size=4><strong>feedback</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> on this site is greatly appreciated.</strong></font></p>
<hr>
<p align=center><strong>[ </strong><a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/index.htm"><strong>Home</strong></a><strong> | </strong><a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/news.htm"><strong>What's New</strong></a><strong> | </strong><a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/toc.htm"><strong>TOC</strong></a><strong> | </strong><a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/feedback.htm"><strong>Feedback</strong></a><strong> | </strong><a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/search.htm"><strong>Search</strong></a><strong> ]</strong></p>
<hr>
<p><strong>Last Revision:&#160;November 6, 1996</strong></p>
</body>

