<title>391-3-12 Duties of the Small Business Ombudsman Office.</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#0000FF" vlink="#808099" alink="#FF0000">
<h4>391-3-12 Duties of the Small Business Ombudsman Office.</h4>
The small business stationary source technical and environmental compliance
office, in order to effectively represent small businesses, shall
carry out the following duties or responsibilities:
<ol type=a>
<li>Participate in and sponsor meetings and conferences with State/local
regulatory officials, industry groups, and small business representatives;
<li>Aid in the dissemination of information (i.e., upcoming air
regulations, control technologies, etc.) to small businesses and
other interested parties;
<li>Review and provide comments and recommendations to the Chief
of the Air Protection Branch regarding the development and
implementation of regulations that impact small businesses;
<li>Facilitate and promote the participation of small businesses
in the development of new regulations that impact small businesses;
<li>Aid in investigating and resolving complaints and disputes
from small businesses against the Air Protection Branch;
<li>Refer small businesses to the appropriate technical specialists
in the Air Protection Branch where they may obtain information
and assistance on affordable alternative technologies, process
changes, products and operational methods to help reduce air pollution
and accidental releases;
<li>Arrange for and assist in the preparation of public information
documents by the Air Protection Branch and attempt to ensure that
the language is readily understandable by the lay person;
<li>Work with trade associations and small businesses to bring
about voluntary compliance with air quality rules and regulations;
<li>Periodically review the work and services provided by the
Air Protection Branch with trade associations and small business
representatives;
<li>Provide confidential assistance, by telephone or otherwise,
on individual source problems and grievances;
<li>Interface with Regional and State offices of the Small Business
Administration, the Department of Commerce and/or other federal
agencies that may have programs to financially assist small businesses
in need of funds to comply with environmental regulations;
<li>Interface with private sector financial institutions to assist
small businesses in locating sources of funds to comply with Air
Protection Branch's requirements and Air Quality Control Rules;
<li>Assist in providing reports to higher authorities and the
public regarding the applicability of the requirements of the
Clean Air Act Amendments to small businesses; and
<li>Serve as the Secretariat for the development and dissemination
of small business advisory panel reports and advisory opinions,
and provide administrative and logistical support to the small
business advisory panel.  The small business advisory panel shall consist
of seven members.  Each member shall be appointed to serve a term of four
years and until his successor is appointed.  If a vacancy is created due
to death or resignation, the proper authority shall appoint a successor
within 90 days.  No member shall serve on the panel for more than two
consecutive terms; and
<li>Carry out any and all duties and responsibilities which may
be delegated to the small business stationary source technical
and environmental compliance program pursuant to O.C.G.A. Section
12-9-25.
</ol>
<hr>
<P>
<font size=2>
Authority: The Georgia Air Quality Act, O.C.G.A. Sec. 12-9-1,
et seq. History. Original Rule entitled &quot;Duties of the Small
Business Ombudsman Office&quot; adopted. F. Nov. 2,1992; eff.
Nov. 22,1992.
</font>
</DOC>
